comment: (collectionOfPerformersOfAction ACTION COLL) relates, by definition, ACTION to the collection of individuals, IND, such that (performedBy ACTION IND). This the the corresponding predicate to PerformerOfFn.
label: Collection Of Performers Of Action
collectionOfPerformersOfAction

comment: (connectedAlongLength OBJ1 OBJ2) means that #$LongAndThin OBJ1 is connectedTo OBJ2 along all, or almost all, of their mutual lengths.
label: Connected Along Length
connectedAlongLength

comment: An afterslot relating a SKSConnectionSpecification to the connection protocol by which we will connect to its server.
label: Connection Protocol For SKS
connectionProtocolForSKS

comment: (isLeaderOf PERSON1 PERSON2) holds just in case PERSON1 and PERSON2 are members of the same organization, ORG, and (hasLeaders ORG PERSON1) and (usually) (not (hasLeaders ORG PERSON2)) holds.
label: follower
isLeaderOf

comment: An ActorSlot and (typed) specialization of buyer. Where BUYING is an instance of (BuyingFn HumanResidence) and BUYER is a HumanAdult, (homeBuyer BUYING BUYER) means that BUYER is a buyer in BUYING.
label: home buyer
homeBuyer

comment: (contraindicatedTreatmentTypeForActivityType PROCEDURE-TYPE ACTIVITY-TYPE) means that, if PROCEDURE is an instance of PROCEDURE-TYPE performedBy AGENT, and SUBJECT is the subjectOfMedicalProcedure_Unique of PROCEDURE, the fact that SUBJECT regularly performs (is the performedBy in) instances of ACTIVITY-TYPE at the time of PROCEDURE implies a (MediumToHighAmountFn Likelihood_QuantityType) that PROCEDURE will be a failure (failureForAgents) for AGENT.
label: Contraindicated Treatment Type For Activity Type
contraindicatedTreatmentTypeForActivityType

comment: The predicate insMarketedAs relates a type of product to a category in which it is marketed. (insMarketedAs PRODTYPE MKTCAT) means that (at least some) elements of the ProductType PRODTYPE are typically marketed to potential consumers as belonging to the ProductTypeByMarketCategory MKTCAT. For example, instances of FishingPole are marketed in the SportingGoodsMarketCategory; instances of SparkPlug are marketed in the StandardAutoMarketCategory; and instances of installing a computer network are marketed in the ComputerHardwareServiceMC.
label: Ins Marketed As
insMarketedAs

comment: A binary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln4_1 RELN BINPRED) means that a formula built from RELN (i.e. a "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence and CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the fourth and first arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARG4 ARG1) holds. For further explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more general quaternary predicate interArgReln, which has two argument-places for specifying the pair of RELN's arguments that must be related by BINPRED.
label: Inter Arg Reln 4 1
interArgReln4-1
Datum For Coordinate System
datumForCoordinateSystem
comment: (datumForCoordinateSystem DATUM SYSTEM) means that DATUM is the GeographicDatum upon which an object's coordinates in SYSTEM are referenced.
(expertUsageType TOOL COLLECTION) holds if COLLECTION is the collection of people who are expert users of TOOL. See also the corresponding function ExpertUsageFn.
label: Expert Usage Type
expertUsageType

comment: (containsInstructionsForActionType IBT TYPE) means that IBT contains instructions for performing an activity of type, TYPE. For example, (containsInstructionsForActionType InstructionSheet392 (MakingFn (ModelFn Airplane))) means that InstructionSheet392 contains instructions for performing the activity of making a model airplane.
label: Contains Instructions For Action Type
containsInstructionsForActionType

comment: (expectedAttritionForActionType ACT_TYPE QUANT) means that in the context, the expected attrition-level of a military action ACT that is of ACT_TYPE is QUANT. See also expectedAttritionForAction.
label: Expected Attrition For Action Type
expectedAttritionForActionType

comment: An expression of the form (cycLParsedTo TRANS EXPRESSION) means that the quoted CycLExpression EXPRESSION is generated as a translation during the IBTTranslating TRANS.
label: Cyc L Parsed To
cycLParsedTo

comment: A KEFacilitationPredicate and a specialization of keGenlsRelevantPreds. (keGenlsStrongSuggestionPreds COL BINPRED) means that for every known (i.e. reified-in-the-KB) specialization SPEC of COL, it is strongly suggested that there be some THING such that (BINPRED SPEC THING) is known in the Knowledge Base.
label: Ke Genls Strong Suggestion Preds
keGenlsStrongSuggestionPreds

comment: (instructionsUsed_IBT EVENT INS) means that the instructions INS are directly used in EVENT in some way.
label: Instructions Used IBT
instructionsUsed-IBT

comment: (infectingOccursAt INFECTING REGION) means that the InfectingEvent INFECTING occurs at the AnimalBodyRegion REGION. REGION is the place on the body of the infected Animal where the pathogen causing the Infection enters.
label: infection entry point
infectingOccursAt

comment: (cblMustReason MUST-COMMAND EXPRESSION) means that if CycBehaviorLanguage MUST-COMMAND throws an assertin error, then EXPRESSION is evaluated as the reason.
label: Cbl Must Reason
cblMustReason

comment: A BinaryRolePredicate that relates an instance of SearchingAnInformationStore to an InformationStore that is searched in that event.
label: Information Store Searched
informationStoreSearched
Html Source Of
htmlSourceOf
comment: (htmlSourceOf SOURCE DOC) means that SOURCE, an HTMLSource, is the source of DOC, an instance of either TextString or GraphicalStructure. SOURCE generates DOC on most web browsers.

(evidentialSupportForPhenomena_AgentUnspecified PHENOM AMOUNT) allows us to say that there is AMOUNT of evidence supporting the existence of PHENOM, without requiring us to specifiy who has this evidence. This is useful for parsing English sentences, which frequently omit references to the "whoever" that has the evidence. See also evidentialSupportForPhenomena and evidentialSupportForBelief.
label: Evidential Support For Phenomena Agent Unspecified
evidentialSupportForPhenomena-AgentUnspecified

comment: (doctrinalRulesOfOrganization MILITARYORG FORMULA) means that FORMULA is a doctrinal, standard rule of combat or other action in MILITARYORG. Most often, they are meant as guidelines and goals, not as actual expectations of actions.
label: Doctrinal Rules Of Organization
doctrinalRulesOfOrganization

comment: A BinaryPredicate that relates an instance of Organization to a Person. (doubleAgentInOrg ORG PERSON) means that PERSON is a member of ORG and is also secretly a member of another organization that is a rival or opponent of ORG and PERSON uses his position in ORG to provide information to the other organization.
label: double agent
doubleAgentInOrg

comment: (clinicalFormMostCommon_Infection INF-GEN-TYPE INF-SPEC-TYPE) means that ifan infection INF is known to be an instance of INF-GEN-TYPE, it is extremely likely, absent information to support the conclusion (not (isa INF INF-SPEC-TYPE)), that (isa INF INF-SPEC-TYPE).
label: Clinical Form Most Common Infection
clinicalFormMostCommon-Infection

comment: (contenders COMP AGENT) indicates that AGENT, a competing agent in the Competition COMP, is considered by anyone who is knowledgeable about the competition to have a good possibility of winning.
label: contender
contenders
Desirability Of Target For Terrorist Attack
desirabilityOfTargetForTerroristAttack
comment: (desirabilityOfTargetForTerroristAttack OBJ QUANT) relates an object OBJ to the degree QUANT to which it is a desirable target for a terrorist attack.

The predicate imapServer is used to indicate the source of information for a particular EMailReceiving. (imapServer RECEIVING SERVER) means that in the EMailReceiving RECEIVING, the email transferred is pulled down from the IMAPServer_Network SERVER, usually to the intended recipient's client machine.
label: Imap Server (binary role predicate)
imapServer

comment: (hasBaseStrengthGreaterThan BASE1 BASE2) holds just in case BASE1 is a stronger Base than BASE2. For instance, (hasBaseStrengthGreaterThan SodiumHydroxide (ChemicalSubstanceFn HydroxideIon)) holds because sodium hydroxide is a stronger base than the hydroxide ion.
label: stronger base of a pair
hasBaseStrengthGreaterThan

comment: (infectionReservoir ORG INFECTION) relates a type of infection INFECTION to the reservoir ORG that may carry it. The reservoir is an alternate or passive host that harbors a pathogenic organism, but does not necessarily suffer from the infection itself. It is, however, a source from which the infection can spread. For example, rats are the infectionReservoir of the BubonicPlague. The rats transmit the infection to fleas, the infectionTypeHasVectorTypes of the BubonicPlague, which in turn infect humans.
label: Infection Reservoir
infectionReservoir

comment: A DocumentationPredicate and a specialization of #$cyclistNotes that is used to enter HumanCyclists' explanations of their encodings of given assigned queries in the formulas (cf. InferenceSentenceParameter) of the respective CycLQuerySpecifications.
label: Cyclification Notes
cyclificationNotes

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function FlanksOfUnitFn. (flanksOfUnit X (FlanksOfUnitFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Flanks Of Unit
flanksOfUnit

comment: (infectionAffectsPart INFECTION PART) means that the AnimalBodyPart of the host affected by the Infection INFECTION is PART.
label: infection site
infectionAffectsPart

comment: (derivedObligations SPEC OBLIG) means that the instance of Obligation OBLIG is motivated by, gets its normative force from, or has as its purpose the satisfaction of the NormativeSpecification SPEC, typically an instance of Agreement or CodeOfConduct. This is a distinct relation from normativeSpecificationParts which would express a partonomic relation between the content of SPEC and the content of OBLIG.
label: Derived Obligation
derivedObligation

comment: (cblRewards WITH-LEARNING-COMMAND LIST) means CycBehaviorLanguage WITH-LEARNING-COMMAND allocates rewards as specified in LIST.
label: Cbl Rewards
cblRewards

comment: (eventToInterrupt_SitType EVT SIT_TYPE) means that, in the planning context, it is part of the purpose of EVT that a situation of type SIT_TYPE should cease to obtain at some point in EVENT but that a situation of type SIT_TYPE should become true again sometime before the end of EVENT.
label: Event To Interrupt Sit Type
eventToInterrupt-SitType

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function HandlingFn. (handling X (HandlingFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Handling (predicate that is functional in its second argument)
handling

comment: (contraindicatedDrug AILMENT DRUG) means that DRUG is contraindicated in patients suffering from AilmentCondition AILMENT.
label: Contraindicated Drug
contraindicatedDrug
Common Modality Ft Theorems Prop Dual
commonModalityFt-Theorems-Prop-Dual
Expected Value
expectedValue
comment: The expected value of this distribution. Not the mode or mean.

(chemicalFormulaString CPD STING) means that STRING is the standard chemical formula abbreviation for CPD. The generation code handles subscripts and superscripts, so in these assertions, numbers and signs indicating electronic charge should be put in parentheses. Examples: H(-) and ASO4(3-).
label: Chemical Formula String
chemicalFormulaString

comment: (derivedLiteraryWork WORK DERIVED) means that the literary work WORK is derived from the literary work DERIVED. There are no generally accepted criteria for when this relation obtains between two works. Nonetheless, there may be contexts in which there are criteria for the applciation of this predicate. Perhaps in a type of naive context, one literary work is not derived from another if, when the original contains fictional characters, the derived work does not have some character which is 'based on' some character in the original.
label: Derived Literary Work
derivedLiteraryWork

comment: (favors_SitType AGENT SITTYPE) means that AGENT favors or approves of a situation of type SITTYPE. That is, AGENT wants either (i) a pre-existing situation of type SITTYPE to continue or (ii) a situation of type SITTYPE to come about. We assume that if an agent favors a particular kind of temporal situation, s/he favors any more general kind of temporal situation.
label: Favors Sit Type
favors-SitType

comment: (keGenlsConsiderationPreds COL BIN-PRED) means that for every specialization SPEC-COL of COL, it should be considered whether there is some VALUE such that (BIN-PRED SPEC-COL VALUE) is known in the KB.
label: Ke Genls Consideration Preds
keGenlsConsiderationPreds

comment: (in_Floating OBJ LIQUID) means that the SolidTangibleThing OBJ is floating on the surface of the LiquidTangibleThing LIQUID. Thus, (in_Floating OBJ LIQUID) implies that OBJ is buoyant and that OBJ is partly immersed (see the predicate in_ImmersedPartly) in LIQUID.
label: In-Floating
in-Floating

comment: This proposition becomes true during this time period.  For example, Liz drank three cups of coffee between 8 and 9 am.
label: Holds Over
holdsOver

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function Deci. (deciVersionOf X (Deci X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Deci Version Of
deciVersionOf

comment: (formularyDrugs ?formulary ?drug) means that ?drug is covered under the insurance plan associated with ?formulary.
label: Formulary Drugs
formularyDrugs

comment: (conceptOfDomain ?CONCEPT ?DOMAIN) means that ?CONCEPT is associated with the domain, ?DOMAIN, either because it is one of the core concepts in the domain (see coreConceptOfDomain), or because it is required in order to state useful facts about a concept which is actually part of DOMAIN (see peripheralConceptOfDomain). conceptOfDomain is a common generalization (genlPreds) of both coreConceptOfDomain and peripheralConceptOfDomain.
label: related concept
conceptOfDomain

comment: X is indirectly acquainted with Y if X knows (is acquainted with) someone who works for Y, someone who has dealt with Y, etc. E.g., X meets and chats with someone who works for company Y and they talk about company Y --- then, X can be assumed to have be indirectlyAcquaintedWith with company Y. X may also be more directly acquainted with Y.
label: indirect acquaintance
indirectlyAcquaintedWith

comment: (highestEducationLevel PERSON EDU-LEVEL) states that PERSON's highest educational level is EDU-LEVEL. If they received a degree it is the level of the highest degree received. If they made it to a particular grade and no further, then it is that grade level. For example, assuming RalphWiggum_FictionalCharacter never makes it out of the second grade, then (highestEducationLevel RalphWiggum_FictionalCharacter FirstGradeLevel) holds as well as (highestEducationLevel RalphWiggum_FictionalCharacter ElementaryLevel).
label: Highest Education Level
highestEducationLevel

comment: A PathSystemCycLConstant that is a specialization of nodeInSystem. (deadEndInSystem END SYS) means that END is a dead-end node in the PathSystem SYS. A node END in SYS is a dead-end node in SYS if there is exactly one link LINK in SYS that END is on and END is not on any loop in SYS. One easy way to illustrate a deadend END in SYS is to picture it as a node with only one path (possibly very "short") in the system through which one can approach or leave END. Note that no totally isolated node in SYS can be a deadend in SYS, nor can any point in SYS that is on a loop in SYS. If there is no specified path-system in which the path ends, but the ending is a dead end of a Path_Customary like a road or wire, then use pathTerminus instead.
label: Dead End In System
deadEndInSystem

comment: An ActorSlot that is a specialization of preActors (q.v.). This predicate is used to indicate the starting point of a particular movement from one place to another. (fromLocation MOVE LOC) means that LOC is where some salient moving-object (see objectMoving) in the Translocation MOVE is found at the beginning of MOVE and is where it begins this motion. This moving-object might or might not be Stationary at LOC at the beginning of MOVE. If MOVE is a single-pathway translation (see Translation_SingleTrajectory), then each of its salient moving-objects is found at LOC when MOVE starts. If MOVE has multiple movers and multiple pathways (see Translation_MultiTrajectory), then at least some of the moving-objects can be found at LOC when MOVE starts. If MOVE is a flow (such as a river flowing, a wind blowing, a tornado, a typhoon, some clouds moving, or air filling your lungs when you take a breath; see FluidFlow_Translation), then at least some portion of the fluid moving-object can be found at LOC when MOVE starts. See also motionPathway_Complete and pathConnects.
label: origin
fromLocation
subPropertyOf: location of some of the event

comment: (executableByNotAmenable_Type FILE-TYPE ACCOUNT) means that it is expected that the account ACCOUNT would not be able to execute (see executableBy) any files of the type FILE-TYPE.
label: Executable By Not Amenable Type
executableByNotAmenable-Type

comment:
A binary #$InferenceCompletenessPredicate that can apply to a predicate and a specified argument-place. (grosslyIncompleteWithArgNotFullyBound PRED N) means that for any sequence SEQ such that PRED holds of SEQ, the Cyc inference engine can provide through removal tactics , at best, a minimal range of the values (VALUE-1, VALUE-2, ..., VALUE-K) such that these values are the Nth elements of SEQ.

(grosslyIncompleteWithArgNotFullyBound PRED N) also means that the Cyc inference engine will treat as "grossly incomplete" any removal tactic for a problem with PRED in the arg0 position and with the Nth argument position not fully bound.

Cf. grosslyIncompleteWithAllArgsNotFullyBound and grosslyIncompleteWithAnyArgsNotFullyBound.
label: Grossly Incomplete With Arg Not Fully Bound
grosslyIncompleteWithArgNotFullyBound
Cyc L Query Answer Binding Set
cycLQueryAnswerBindingSet
comment: An assertion of the form (cycLQueryAnswerBindingSet. QUERY BINDING-SET) states that the CycQueryRunning QUERY, an event, returned the ELInferenceBindingSet BINDING-SET as the set of bindings for the CycLQuerySpecification that was asked during QUERY.

(compressibilityOfObject OBJ DEGREE) indicates how readily the tangible object OBJ can be compressed to a smaller volume. The higher the DEGREE of compressibility, the more easily the object can be compressed to a smaller volume. A related concept is elasticityOfObject.
label: Compressibility Of Object
compressibilityOfObject

comment: This predicate relates two- or three-dimensional circular- or spherical-shaped objects to their diameters, represented as Distances. (diameterOfObject OBJECT DIAMETER) means that he diameter of OBJECT is DIAMETER. See also radius.
label: diameter
diameterOfObject

comment:
A BinaryPredicate that is used to state that a special relation holds between a FacetingCollectionType and a BinaryPredicate -- that the former is "based on" the latter in a specific way.

Where (facets_Generic COL FACET-COL), (facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse FACET-COL BINPRED) means that for all X in FACET-COL, there is a Y such that, by the definition of X, X is the one and only specialization of COL to which Y bears BINPRED.

For example, (facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse PersonTypeByNationality countryOfNationality) means that for all NATIONALITY in PersonTypeByNationality, there is a COUNTRY such that, by the definition of NATIONALITY, NATIONALITY is the one and only specialization of Person to which COUNTRY bears the countryOfNationality relation.

E.g. ItalianPerson, an instance of PersonTypeByNationality, is the one and only specialization of Person to which Italy bears the countryOfNationality relation.

For cases in which the arguments of BINPRED are reversed, see facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPred. See also facetBasedOnBinaryPredInverse and #$SharedNoteOnFacetBasisPredicates.
label: Facet Based On Type Binary Pred Inverse
facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse

comment: This is a form of ist that applies to the specified details of an obligation; ist itself is used for other conditions that are true but not part of the obligation. For example, the fact that Joe is obligated to sweep the floor is ist_Obligation; this requires Joe to be an agent, which is an ist type of condition.
label: Ist-Obligation
ist-Obligation

comment: (fieldsOfCompetence PERSON FIELD) means that the Person PERSON has actual competence and knowledgability in the FieldOfStudy FIELD, or at least is recognized by peers and colleagues in FIELD as being competent in FIELD. See also the related predicates expertRegarding and domainsOfSpecialization.
label: Fields Of Competence
fieldsOfCompetence

comment:
A ComplexTemporalPredicate that is a specialization of both startingDate and endingDate (qq.v.). dateOfEvent relates an event to a Date on or in which it transpired. (dateOfEvent EVENT DATE) means that EVENT both starts and ends during DATE. For example, the sentence 

  (dateOfEvent
        GettysburgAddress_Speech
        (DayFn 19 (MonthFn November (YearFn 1863))))

is true because Lincoln both started and finished that address on the date mentioned.

See also occursDuring.
label: date
dateOfEvent

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function Giga. (gigaVersionOf X (Giga X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Giga Version Of
gigaVersionOf

comment: (contraindicatedTreatmentTypeForConditionType TREATMENT-TYPE CONDITION-TYPE) means that TREATMENT-TYPE is contraindicated in patients with the AilmentCondition CONDITION-TYPE.
label: contraindicated treatment
contraindicatedTreatmentTypeForConditionType

comment: (inputIndicatedProduct PRSN PROD-TYPE) means that because of customer input to the Cyc ProductAdvisor about her preferences of what type of item to purchase for the Person PRSN, it can be inferred that ProductType PROD-TYPE is positively indicated for PRSN. In contrast to (explicitlyIndicatedProduct PRSN STATED-TYPE), which represents a customer's stated preference for ProductType STATED-TYPE, (inputIndicatedProduct PRSN PROD-TYPE) represents a lesser degree of positive indication because PROD-TYPE is derived via genls from STATED-TYPE. For example, suppose a customer using the Cyc Product Advisor gives a positive response to a question of the form, 'Are you interested in toys?'. This response would result in the following assertion being provably true in #$TheSessionMt, (inputIndicatedProduct TheRecipient ActionFigure_Toy), because (genls ActionFigure_Toy Toy). Assertions using this predicate indicate a weaker degree of suitability than assertions using explicitlyIndicatedProduct. For example, from the fact that the customer states that she is interested in buying a Toy, it should follow that all subcollections of Toy have some positive indication, but she might not be interested in ActionFigure_Toy. So the degree to which ActionFigure_Toy is indicated should be less than the degree to which Toy is indicated.
label: Input Indicated Product
inputIndicatedProduct

comment: (dailyHighTemperature PLACE TEMP) means that the Temperature TEMP is the high temperature for a day at the GeographicalRegion PLACE. dailyHighTemperature is typically used for a specified period of time (e.g., a particular day or a specific season); it may be used with generic temperature ranges as well as precise temperatures. Examples: using holdsIn, we can say that Austin's temperature for 7/20/96 is 102 degrees Fahrenheit; or we can say that for any SummerSeason, Austin's [typical] dailyHighTemperature is VeryHot.
label: Daily High Temperature
dailyHighTemperature
Criterial For Terrain Tactical Role Negative
criterialForTerrainTacticalRole-Negative
comment: (criterialForTerrainTacticalRole_Negative TERRAIN-TYPE SET-TERM) means that membership in SET-TERM constitutes a negative criteria for playing the tactical role associated with TERRAIN-TYPE. SET-TERM is a set-denoting term constructed with TheSetOf plus a sentence. So: if an instance X of GeographicalThing satisfies that sentence, hence belongs to SET-TERM, that counts in favor of using X tactically as a TERRAIN-TYPE in the given planning context. Contrast with criterialForTerrainTacticalRole_Positive.
A predicate corresponding to the function FreeTourTimeInFn. (freeTourTimeIn X (FreeTourTimeInFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Free Tour Time In
freeTourTimeIn

comment: equivalentHosts relates one ComputationalSystem to another. (equivalentHosts SYSTEM1 SYSTEM2) means that the users (except users with root access) of SYSTEM1 can access their accounts on SYSTEM2 without having to re-enter their Username or Password_Computer. Usually host equivalency is configured by a system administrator using the file /etc/hosts.equiv. Compare this predicate to equivalentRoot.
label: Equivalent Hosts
equivalentHosts

comment: (connectedAround OBJ1 OBJ2) means that OBJ1 is connectedTo OBJ2 in a circuit around OBJ2. Portions of OBJ2 are open to the environment on both sides (three dimensionally) of OBJ1.
label: Connected Around
connectedAround

comment: A FirstOrderCollectionPredicate and a specialization of dietPrescribes that relates a given DietProgram (q.v.) to a type of food or drink whose consumption the diet prescribes or recommends exclusively. (dietPrescribesExclusively DIET STUFFTYPE) means that DIET instructs the dieter to consume only STUFFTYPE (some specialization of EdibleStuff). For example, a fasting diet might prescribe clear liquids exclusively. See also dietRestricts and its specialization dietProscribes.
label: Diet Prescribes Exclusively
dietPrescribesExclusively

comment: (frequencyStabilityOfTransmitter RAD FREQ) means that the transmitter TRANS, an instance of Transmitter, has a frequency drift of FREQ.
label: Frequency Stability Of Transmitter
frequencyStabilityOfTransmitter

comment: (informationStorageUnit STORING STORE) means that in the information storage situation STORING, STORE is an information storage unit.
label: Information Storage Unit
informationStorageUnit
Has Capability
hasCapability
comment: (hasCapability OBJ CAP) means that OBJ has the capability CAP.

A predicate corresponding to the function ChemicalReaction_IntentionalFn. (chemicalReaction_IntentionalOf X (ChemicalReaction_IntentionalFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Chemical Reaction Intentional Of
chemicalReaction-IntentionalOf

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function DestinationNameFn. (destinationName X (DestinationNameFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Destination Name
destinationName

comment: (dataTypeExploitedBy FAULT DATA-TYPE) means that to take advantage of the #$SoftwareFault,FAULT, one uses as an implement data that is of the type DATA-TYPE. For example, (dataTypeExploitedBy AutomaticAttachmentExecutionFault EMailAttachment) means that to exploit an automatic attachment execution fault, one uses an e-mail attachment.
label: Data Type Exploited By
dataTypeExploitedBy

comment: A predicate that relates a specialization of MultiIndividualAgent_Intelligent INDUSTRY-TYPE to the specialization of TemporalThing, TYPE, of which INDUSTRY-TYPE is the business of TYPE. This is a broad relation, and INDUSTRY-TYPE will include all of the people and activities for the business, not just the production of instances of TYPE.
label: Industry Of Type
industryOfType

comment: A FamilyRelationSlot that is a specialization of both cohabitants and relatives. (cohabitingFamilyMembers MEMBER1 MEMBER2) means that MEMBER1 and MEMBER2 are members the same family (see Family_SocialEntity) -- such as relatives, spouses, or in-laws -- that live with one another. See also FamilyCohabitationUnit. Note that MEMBER1 and MEMBER2 might be Animals of any type whatsoever; although in certain contexts (e.g. HumanSocialLifeMt) they are presupposed to be Persons.
label: cohabiting family member
cohabitingFamilyMembers

comment:
A symmetric, reflexive RelativeLocationalPredicates that relates straight lines (see Line_Straight) that lie in the same plane. (coplanarLines LINE1 LINE2) is true if and only if there is a Plane that spatiallySubsumes both LINE1 and LINE2.

See also coplanarPoints.
label: Coplanar Lines
coplanarLines

comment: A FamilyRelationSlot. (fosterSons PARENT SON) means that SON is a foster son of PARENT.
label: foster son
fosterSons

comment: (composerOfMusicalCW AGENT CW) means that AGENT is the composer of CW (a MusicalComposition).
label: Composer Of Musical CW
composerOfMusicalCW

comment: (eventToPrevent_SitType EVT SITTYPE) means that, in the planning context, a Situation satisfying the description of SITTYPE must NOT come about at any time during the course of EVT in order for EVT to count as 'successful'. It is presupposed that no Situation of type SITTYPE obtains at the start of SIT.
label: Event To Prevent Sit Type
eventToPrevent-SitType

comment: A StrictlyFunctionalSlot predicate that relates a given set or collection (see SetOrCollection) to its extension: the set consisting of all of (and only) its elements (see elementOf). (extent SETORCOL SET) means that every element of SETORCOL is an element of SET and every element of SET is an element of SETORCOL. If SETORCOL happens to be a set (see Set_Mathematical) itself, then SET and SETORCOL are identical (see equals), as sets are identified and distinguished strictly in terms of their elements. Conversely, if SETORCOL happens to be a collection (see Collection), then SET and SETORCOL are distinct (see different), as no collection is a set. See also coextensionalSetOrCollections.
label: Extent (antisymmetric binary predicate)
extent

comment: (effectiveSterilizationMeansFor MICROBETYPE STUFFTYPE) means that, absent evidence to the contrary, a given person can perform a killing of an instance of MICROBETYPE by means of an instance of STUFFTYPE with a high level of Effectiveness.
label: Effective Sterilization Means For
effectiveSterilizationMeansFor

comment: An assertion of the form (ibtKeyWords IBT STRING) means that the InformationBearingThing IBT represents the SubLString STRING as a keyword for understanding its topic or content.
label: Ibt Key Words
ibtKeyWords

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function InventingFn. (inventing X (InventingFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Inventing (predicate that is functional in its second argument)
inventing

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function DrugFn. (drug X (DrugFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Drug (predicate that is functional in its second argument)
drug

comment: (insertShellCommandIntoDataStringForProgram AGENT PROGRAM) means that AGENT constructs a data string intended for a copy of PROGRAM, and that data string contains a command to spawn a user or root shell on the computer on which the copy of PROGRAM is running.

comment:
A binary predicate that relates a spatial thing to the direction in which it's pointing. (direction_Pointing OBJ DIR) means that the intrinsic pointing axis of OBJ points in the direction DIR (represented as a UnitVectorInterval).

Pointing axes may be ascribed to certain objects, especially in relation to their functions or uses; e.g. to indicate direction (as with a pointer stick or a compass needle), to cause motion in a certain direction (as with a gun or a train), or to be accessed from a certain direction (as with a cupboard or a couch).

Some objects, like the train and the cupboard, point in the same direction that they face (see facesDirection). Other objects, such as a tower, point and face in different directions. Still other objects, such as a sewing needle, point in a certain direction but don't face in any direction at all.
label: Direction-Pointing
direction-Pointing

Note that ENDS and GOES-ON might not temporally intersect (see temporallyIntersects); though they must intersect if GOES-ON is temporallyContinuousDuring.

A binary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln1_2 RELN BINPRED) means that a formula built from RELN (i.e. a "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence and CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the first and second arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARG1 ARG2) holds. For example, (interArgReln1_2 relativePosition cotemporal) means that the first and second arguments in relativePosition assertions must be cotemporal. For an explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more general quaternary predicate interArgReln, which has two argument-places for specifying the pair of RELN's arguments that must be related by BINPRED.
label: Inter Arg Reln 1 2

comment: The predicate governedByAgreement relates an event to an agreement that stipulates something with respect to it, such as certain conditions that are to hold during the event, or whether the event should or should not occur. (governedByAgreement EVT AGR) means that some aspects of the instance of HumanActivity EVT are controlled by, or 'under the jurisdiction of', the instance of Agreement AGR. For example, a BuyingGroup may have SalesContracts with its suppliers that specify what prices may be charged for goods bought by members of the group during the agreement period. But note that an event's being governed by an agreement does not entail that the event conforms to what the agreement stipulates: an act that violates the agreement is still governed by it.

The predicate eventOccursNear relates an event to its approximate location. (eventOccursNear EVENT LOC) means that EVENT occurs at or near (see near) LOC. eventOccursNear is useful when the more exact location is unknown, hard to specify, or not worth reifying; otherwise use eventOccursAt. For example, eventOccursNear could be used to CycLify "Bob was cycling by the dam", "We played checkers near the TV", and "He is standing by the horse's hind legs". See the #$cyclistNotes for ideas on how to formalize this.

The main difference between desires and its specialization hopes, is that one can desire something that one knows to be true. For example, a thin person can desire to be (i.e. remain) thin. In contrast, one can hope only for what one is uncertain about. Thus hopes is a specialization of hasEpistemicEmotion while desires is not.

See also goals and intends.

comment: An ActorSlot for objects that serve physically to constrain the movements of other objects in MovementEvents, either by affecting their trajectories, by limiting or reducing their speeds, by determining the general types of movements they undergo (e.g. rotational vs. translational), or by having some other constrictive effect on their motions. (granuleOfTemporalStuff STUFFTYPE OBJTYPE) means that the stuff-like collection STUFFTYPE has as its temporal granules (or granularity level) instances of the object-like collection OBJTYPE. If some collection is temporally stuff-like, that means that the instances of that collection can be divided temporally, and the temporal slices remaining will still be instances of that collection; e.g., a time slice of some instance of Person is still a person, and a temporal slice of a walking process is still a walking process (cf. TemporalStuffType). Such division cannot always go on indefinitely, however: eventually, division of something temporally stuff-like will result in the temporally object-like 'granules' out of which the stuff-like thing is composed. For instances, division of a walking process would eventually result in individual steps. At this level of division or below, the remaining temporal slices do NOT count as instances of the temporal stuff-type from which they were divided. This may seem counter-intuitive, but since the individual temporal granules of a temporal stuff typically do NOT have most of the properties that the groups made of the granules have (including the property of being temporally stuff-like), we do not count the individual granules as instances of the collection of which they are granules. See also granuleOfSpatialStuff.
label: Granule Of Temporal Stuff
granuleOfTemporalStuff

That a classification system is focally a system of classifying some type TYPE does not mean that every concept in the system is an instance of TYPE. For example, an ontology (Ontology) will also contain relations and operators that enable it to represent facts and rules, where those facts and rules will serve primarily to define the instances of TYPE that occur in the ontology, and, to a lesser extent, to define the concepts that are needed to define those instances of TYPE. For example, an ontology of biological species might also contain concepts, such as height, weight, and anatomical concepts that, though not the focus of the ontology per se, must have some representation in the ontology to be of use in representing biological species.

comment: A FamilyRelationSlot and specialization of coreRelatives that relates a given person or other animal to each of his or her children. (children PARENT CHILD) means that PARENT fulfills the role of parent with respect to CHILD. Note that, in the case of humans, PARENT's being one of CHILD's biological parents (see biologicalOffspring) is neither necessary nor sufficient for this. Thus, CHILD might be an adopted child (see adoptedChildren), stepchild, or foster child of PARENT's. Conversely, a biological parent who has given a child up for adoption would not normally be related to that child by the predicate children. In the case of nonhuman animals (see NonPersonAnimal), however, children holds between two given creatures if and only if biologicalOffspring does.

comment: A ConnectionPredicate and thus a specialization of connectedTo. (connectedTo_SemiRigidly OBJ1 OBJ2) means that there is a physical connection between OBJ1 and OBJ2 that is flexibile enough to permit limited (and only limited) movement of OBJ1 and/or OBJ2 around the point of connection. Positive examples include a front cover hinged to the spine of a book (see flapHingedTo) and the gall bladder's attachment to the liver. Negative examples include a wheel's connection to its axle and a door hinged to a door frame; in both cases the freedom of movement derives from geometrical or mechanical properties of the objects and their connectors, rather than from the flexibity of the connected objects. Note that all flexible connections place some limit on the freedom of relative motion they allow. An extreme example (in the "more free" direction) is the connection between the propeller and fuselage of a rubberband-powered toy airplane.
label: Connected To Semi Rigidly
connectedTo-SemiRigidly

comment: goalSituationType is a simple but powerful means of representing a desired event type. This predicate relates a #$GoalSituation to a Collection which has Situation as a genls. (goalSituationType GOAL-SITUATION DESIRED-SITUATION-TYPE) means that at least one Agent_PartiallyTangible (such agents are identified by #$goalAgent) has a goal, desire, want or need to play a role (this role is identified by goalRoleSlot) in some instance of DESIRED-SITUATION-TYPE. For example (goalSituationType `GoalSituation001' TakingAShower) means that during `GoalSituation001' any #$goalAgent for `GoalSituation001' wants to play some role in TakingAShower. If (goalRoleSlot `GoalSituation002' performedBy) is also asserted, then this specifies that any #$goalAgent for `GoalSituation001' wishes to play the role of performedBy in some element of TakingAShower. In other words, "someone wishes to take a shower". If one wishes to assert that "Fred wishes to take a shower." then one would add the assertion (#$goalAgent `GoalSituation002' `Fred'). Compared with #$goalSituationSuccessIf predicate has limitations in terms of expressivity. However, it has more inferencing power. See (VersusFn (TheSet goalSituationType goalRoleSlot) #$goalSituationSuccessIf) for more on this issue.
label: Goal Situation Type
goalSituationType

A predicate that relates a particular rotational motion event to the total angular distance travelled by the moving object (see the predicate objectMoving) in that event. (distanceOfRotation ROT DIST) means that in the event ROT, the objectMoving travels the angular distance DIST. Note that DIST is the total angular distance travelled by the objectMoving, and not just the net angular displacement of the objectMoving. So if a person spins around ten times, then the distanceOfRotation in that spinning event is 3600 degrees, not zero.

A group may or may not have a prototype. A group has only one prototype (if it has any). A prototype exists prior to other members of the group; it may or may not itself be a member of the group (by default, Cyc assumes it is). For example, the prototype for the class of Saturn V rockets; or, Casanova as the prototypical romantic adventurer.

comment: (currentDurationOfStay TRANSPORTER DURATION) holds just in case TRANPORTER is stopped either between transportation events it is involved in, or between legs of a single trip and the length of time before it starts its next trip or continues on the current trip is DURATION. Note that if TRANSPORTER will no longer be the transporter in any future transportation event, then the duration of the stay will be the length of time remaining until either the transporter is moved from it's last destination or ceases to exist. As time moves forward, DURATION decreases accordingly. So, if this first became true on May 1, and the value for DURATION was 4 days, on May 3, the value for DURATION will be 2 days.

comment: A MetaRelation predicate that relates unary one-to-one functions. (inverseFunctions FUNC1 FUNC2) means that FUNC1 and FUNC2 are the inverses of each other. Thus, for any things X and Y, FUNC1 maps X to Y if and only if FUNC2 maps Y to X. Note that the foregoing condition is necessary but not sufficient for one function's being the inverse of another. This is because Function_Denotationals are understood as being "functions-in-intension", making it theoretically possible for numerically distinct (but extensionally equivalent) functions to satisfy the above condition with respect to a given function. For example, in a context restricted to monogamous heterosexual married people, the inverse of a "HusbandFn" would presumably be the "WifeFn" and not the "BestFriendOfThisManFn", even if the latter two functions happened to be coextensional in that context. See also the corresponding function InverseFunctionFn. To relate a mathematical function (i.e. a MathematicalFunctionOnScalars) to its inverse, see inverseQuantFunctions_Nonsymmetric.
label: Inverse Functions
inverseFunctions

Since individual members of most species typically do not have eyes of different colors (Siamese cats being one exception), eyeColor behaves like a FunctionalSlot (q.v.) with respect to most, but not all, types of animals. See also HumanEyeColor.

comment: (cutNodeInSystem X SYS) means that X is a single node in the ConnectedPathSystem SYS whose removal would cause the system to be disconnected. Thus {X}, i.e., (TheSet X), is a node-cut-set in SYS. That is to say, (cutNodeInSystem X SYS) holds if and only if (nodeCutSetInSystem (TheSet X) SYS) holds. Note that since SYS is a ConnectedPathSystem whenever (cutNodeInSystem X SYS) holds, it is easy to see that (cutNodeInSystem X SYS) holds if and only if (nodeCutMinimalSetInSystem (TheSet X) SYS) holds.
label: Cut Node In System

comment: A binary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln4_3 RELN BINPRED) means that a formula built from RELN (i.e. a "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence and CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the fourth and third arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARG4 ARG3) holds. For further explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more general quaternary predicate interArgReln, which has two argument-places for specifying the pair of RELN's arguments that must be related by BINPRED.

comment: (for_UnderspecifiedLocation ACT GOALLOC) states that an abstract locational relation holds between ACT and GOALLOC, where GOALLOC is a target goal conceptualized as an abstract location. for_UnderspecifiedLocation is thus a specialization of to_UnderspecifiedLocation that views the target location as a goal, abstract or physical. Consider the difference between 'shampoo for greasy hair' and 'shampoo for shiny hair': the former sees 'greasy hair' as a geographical goal (i.e., apply the shampoo to greasy hair) while the latter sees 'shiny hair' as a desired goal (i.e., apply this shampoo if you want shiny hair). This distinction is a subtle one, and not one that can be captured adequately at the level of lexical semantics. Thus we provide for_UnderspecifiedLocation to indicate that GOALLOC should -- when it makes good 'pragmatic' sense to do so -- designate a goal rather than a physical destination.
label: for
for-UnderspecifiedLocation

(distalTo OBJ-1 OBJ-2) means that OBJ-1 lies in the DistalDirection of OBJ-2, with respect to a reference point (see centralReferencePoint) within an object having an AnimalBodyShapeType (often, a Person) that they are located in. This reference point is determined by the location of OBJ-1 and OBJ-2. For example, if OBJ-1 and OBJ-2 are in the CirculatorySystem, the Heart is the point of reference, so (distalTo FredsFemoralArtery FredsAorta) means that Fred's aorta lies between Fred's femoral artery and his heart (see betweenOnPath for the relevant sense of between). Note that (distalTo OBJ-1 OBJ-2) implies that OBJ-2 is proximal to OBJ-1; thus, no distinct predicate is needed to represent "proximal to". OBJ-1 and OBJ-2 are often, but not always, AnimalBodyRegions.
label: Distal To
distalTo

comment:
This predicate is used to state that the value of a fluent remains constant for a fixed object throughout an event. (constantThroughoutEvent_Fluent FLUENT EVENT) is true if and only if for every pair of sub-events SUB1 and SUB2 of EVENT there exist values VAL1 and VAL2 such that if 
(and
  (startsAfterEndingOf SUB1 SUB2)
  (valueOf (MeasurementAtFn FLUENT SUB1) VAL1))
  (valueOf (MeasurementAtFn FLUENT SUB2) VAL2))
it follows that 
(numericallyEquals VAL1 VAL2)
is true. See also decreasesThroughoutEvent_Fluent and increasesThroughoutEvent_Fluent.

comment:
(derivedFrom PRODUCT MATERIAL) means that PRODUCT has been made from MATERIAL by an irreversible process; e.g., an element of Table_PieceOfFurniture may have been derivedFrom an instance of MapleTree.

Note that derivedFrom is not transitive: A particular Door121 may be derived from OakTree53, SandMob442, and several other things. Subsequently, someone may break down the door and make Mallet0234 out of some of the wood and a WindowPane120825 out of some (or all) of the glass. Both Mallet0234 and WindowPane120825 are derivedFrom Door121, but Mallet0234 is not derivedFrom SandMob442, nor is WindowPane120825 derivedFrom OakTree53.
label: derivative
derivedFrom

comment: (coaControlMeasure COAMT SPATIALTHING) means that in the special Course of Action context represented by COAMT, SPATIALTHING has the special status of 'Control Measure'. This means that SPATIALTHING is a coordination feature which aids in the development process of that particular COA. Instances are used in order to to assign responsibilities, coordinate fires and maneuver, and control combat operations. Each control measure can be portrayed graphically. In general, all control measures should be easily identifiable on the ground. Examples of control measures include boundaries, objectives, coordinating points, contact point, and direction of attack. From FM 101-5-1.
label: control measure of the COA
coaControlMeasure

(in_Spiked SPIKE OBJ) means that SPIKE, an object with at least one sharp end, is lodged in OBJ, so that (in_Lodged SPIKE OBJ) holds. comment: (hasAsBoundary REG BOUND) means that BOUND either borders on REG (see bordersOn) or part of the boundary of REG is spatially subsumed by BOUND. It is particularly useful when one wishes to be agnostic about whether BOUND is or is not a sub-region of REG or whether BOUND contains a sub-region which is a sub-region of REG, or whether REG simply borders on (see bordersOn) BOUND. Some examples: (hasAsBoundary Virginia_State PotomacRiver) and (hasAsBoundary Maryland_State PotomacRiver). Whereas the Potomac merely borders on Virginia, the non D.C. portion of the length of the Potomac is a sub-region of Maryland. Alternatively, BOUND can be shared by two regions which border on each other. Thus, since the northern and southern halves of the Red River belong to Oklahoma and Texas respectively, hasAsBoundary is an appropriate relationship between Oklahoma and the Red River as well as between Texas and the Red River. Note that unlike formsBorderBetween, the bounding region need not be thin or small relative to the bounded object(s). Thus, both England and the United States have the Atlantic Ocean as the second argument in hasAsBoundary assertions.

comment:
A specialization of the predicate equivAlgorithms that relates Algorithms (q.v.) to equivalent ones that are structurally similar to them except for possibly being less detailed. (genlAlgorithms SPEC-ALG GENL-ALG) means that SPEC-ALG and GENL-ALG are functionally equivalent algorithms (see equivAlgorithms), and that SPEC-ALG is at least as detailed a sequence of operations as GENL-ALG.

More precisely, for each successive operation OP in GENL-ALG, SPEC-ALG contains (in the same relative position) either OP itself or a series of operations OP1, ..., OPN such that, whenever OP produces output OUT from input IN, then the relative product of OP1, ..., OPN for IN is OUT.

For example, GENL might contain a step that simply says "Sort list L alphabetically", whereas the analogous segment of SPEC-ALG delineates the series of steps involved in doing an alphabetical bubble-sort on L. A third algorithm, which was just like SPEC-ALG except for specifying another type of alphabetizing procedure, would constitute another specialization of GENL. Arguably, corresponding executable code, source code, and pseudocode versions of a given instance of ComputerProgram_CW often use maximal algorithms that are strictly speaking distinct, but ordered by genlAlgorithms.
label: Genl Algorithms
genlAlgorithms

For we allow that distinct things (e.g. a tangible object and the pure space region it occupies) can spatially coincide without sharing any common parts. SpaceRegions that are cospatial, however, are identical (see #$identicalSpaceRegions).

A bit more formally: in the case of a favorable response, AGENT1 has a goal GOAL1 and believes AGENT2 has a goal GOAL2 such that AGENT1 believes that AGENT2 is responsibleFor SIT and also believes that SIT increases the likelihood that GOAL1 will be realized. This predicate is agnostic as to whether DOER does EVENT intentionally or not. Note that DOER need not even be animate or an agent; e.g. the famous vocanic eruption that buried Pompeii was doneBy Mt. Vesuvius. Note also that an event might have more than one doer; consider a chess game.

See the specializations performedBy and bodilyDoer for cases in which the "doer" is, respectively, an Agent_Generic acting deliberately and an Organism_Whole behaving non-deliberately.

comment:
A binary predicate that relates a given KBContentTest (q.v.) to the propositional or otherwise intensional content (see Information_Content) of the question that the test is asking. (kbContentTestQuestion_Content TEST CONTENT) means that TEST asks about CONTENT. If the question being asked in TEST is a "Yes/No" question, then CONTENT will be a Proposition. If the question being asked in TEST is a "what things are such that" question -- i.e. a question that asks for bindings for variables -- then CONTENT will be an intensional property or propositional function.

If TEST has a specific CycL sentence SENT as its InferenceSentenceParameter (q.v.) value, then CONTENT will be (IntensionOfQuerySentenceFn SENT): the intensional meaning of SENT with respect to its potential use in a Cyc query. If TEST is a #$KBContentTest-QueryContentOnly, then any specialization SPECTEST of TEST (see genlKBContentTests) must have CONTENT as its question-content as well; and if SPECTEST has SPECSENT as the value of its InferenceSentenceParameter, then (IntensionOfQuerySentenceFn SPECSENT) will be equal to CONTENT.
label: Kb Content Test Question Content
kbContentTestQuestion-Content

comment:
A TemporalPredicate and MeasurableQuantitySlot (qq.v.) that relates a temporal thing to the length of time (see Time_Quantity) during which it existed, happened, or obtained. (duration TEMPTHING TIME) means that TIME is the amount of time during which TEMPTHING existed (if a SomethingExisting) or happened (if an Event) or obtained (if a StaticSituation).

Note that if TEMPTHING is an instance of TemporallyContinuousThing (q.v.), its duration is the same as its timeSpan (q.v.): the total elapsed time from its start to its end. But if TEMPTHING is discontinuous, its duration is strictly less than its time-span. For example, the playing of the 2004 Super Bowl game has a duration of one hour, but a time-span of several hours.
label: duration

Mx4rvVxE4ZwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Disease Type Symptom Types Necessary And Sufficient
comment:
A specialization of diseaseTypeSymptomTypes_Necessary (q.v.) that relates DiseaseTypes to PhysiologicalConditionTypes that constitute their necessary and sufficient symptoms. (diseaseTypeSymptomTypes_NecessaryAndSufficient DISTYPE SYMPTYPE) means that both (i) each case of DISTYPE involves (as properSubSituations) one or more occurrences of SYMPTYPE and (ii) no occurrence of SYMPTYPE is a proper sub-situation of a case of any other type of disease than DISTYPE. For example, (diseaseTypeSymptomTypes_NecessaryAndSufficient Asthma AsthmaAttack) holds.

Occurrences SYMPTYPE are typically more readily identifiable than the occurrences of DISTYPE that subsume them; hence their usefulfulness in diagnosis and in gauging treatment effectiveness. But note that this is not part of the definition of the predicate diseaseTypeSymptomTypes_NecessaryAndSufficient.
label: Disease Type Symptom Types Necessary And Sufficient

comment: A predicate used for probability statements. (conditionallyIndependent PROPOSITION1 PROPOSITION2) means that, in the applicable Microtheory, PROPOSITION1 and PROPOSITION2 are conditionally independent of each other, that is, truth or falsehood of one does not increase or decrease the derivedProbability that the other is true. They are, in a sense, irrelevant to each other. In most microtheories, generally, the conditionallyIndependent statement means that when all we know in the Microtheory are its accessible domainAssumptions, then the truths of the two formulae are probabilistically independent. See also conditionalProbability and conditionallyIndependentSentences. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.
label: Conditionally Independent
conditionallyIndependent

comment: (contemporaryInArg PRED N) means that the Relation PRED is such that whenever a formula (PRED ... ARGN ...), with ARGN a TemporalThing, is true at a moment in time, it will be the case that the moment belongs to the temporal extent of ARGN (i.e., that ARGN temporally subsumes the moment). For example, it's the case that (contemporaryInArg awareOf 1). So from the assertion (holdsIn (YearFn 1992) (awareOf Fred GeorgeWashington)), we can conclude (given that Fred is a TemporalThing) that Fred was alive throughout (temporally subsumes) 1992. But it's not the case that (contemporaryInArg awareOf 2). And indeed we wouldn't want to conclude that GeorgeWashington was alive throughout 1992. In general (with the qualifications indicated below), an assertion (holdsIn TIME (PRED ... ARGN ...)), with PRED such that (contemporaryInArg PRED N) and ARGN a TemporalThing, licenses the conclusion (temporallySubsumes ARGN TIME). And an assertion (holdsSometimeDuring TIME (PRED ... ARGN ...)) licenses the conclusion (temporallyIntersects ARGN TIME). Although what constitutes a moment can vary with context, for most microtheories explicit considerations of temporal granularity (in this sense) don't come into play. In particular, in the case of most microtheories, one doesn't have to worry about the possibility of gaps in the fabric of time between moments. (Such gaps would undermine the conclusion above about temporal subsumption.) Another qualification is that ARGN is not a IndexicalFirstOrderTerm; in practice, it almost never is. In order for a predicate PRED to be contemporary in its Nth argument-place, the arity of PRED must be greater than or equal to N, and the argument-type of the Nth argument-place of PRED must be non-disjoint with TemporalThing (or, more generally, the intersection of the argument-types of the Nth argument-place of PRED must be non-disjoint with TemporalThing). This is to bar cases in which a predicate would otherwise trivially qualify as contemporary in its Nth argument-place. Note that CoexistingObjectsPredicates are contemporary in both their first and second argument-places, and CotemporalPredicates are contemporary in at least one argument-place.
label: Contemporary In Arg
contemporaryInArg

comment:
A TaxonomicSlotForCollections and a specialization (via genlInverse) of typeGenls (q.v.). This is the most general of the "faceting" predicates. (facets_Generic COL COLTYPE) means that COLTYPE corresponds to one way of dividing COL into subcollections. The instances of COLTYPE are all "the same sort" of subcollection of COL. For example, MovieTypeByGenre facets Movie_CW according to movie-genre; the former's instances thus include such collections as WesternMovie and HorrorMovie. And FunctionTypeByRangeType facets Function_Denotational according to the type of thing a given function returns as values; the former's instances thus include such collections as IndividualDenotingFunction and CollectionDenotingFunction.

Note that generic faceting does not entail that the instances of COLTYPE are mutually disjoint. Thus, a given film might be an instance of both ChildrensMovie and ActionMovie.

Note also that generic faceting does not entail that every instance of COL falls under some instance of COLTYPE. Thus, consider the universal identity function IdentityFn. Its range of values is so broad that it does not fall under any instance of FunctionTypeByRangeType.

Specializations of facets_Generic include facets_Covering, facets_Strict, and facets_Partition, as well as facets_NearCovering, facets_NearStrict, and facets_NearPartition. Whenever possible, one of these more specific predicates should be used.
label: Facets-Generic
facets-Generic

comment: A TaxonomicSlotForCollections (q.v.) that relates a set of collections to the collection whose extent (see extent) is by definition the intersection of the extents of all the collections in that set. (collectionIntersection INTERSECT SET-OF-COLS) means that INTERSECT is the "collection-intersection" of SET-OF-COLS: any given thing THING is an instance of INTERSECT if and only if THING is an instance of every collection that is an element of SET-OF-COLS. It follows that INTERSECT is itself a subcollection of every element of SET-OF-COLS. Note that, since collections are supposed to be "intensionally defined", it is theoretically possible that there be more than one collection having exactly the extent (i.e. set of instances) characterized above. But COL is to be thought of as the collection which _by_definition_ contains all and only the instances common to every collection in SET-OF-COLS. In other words, the criterion for instanceship associated with INTERSECT (i.e. its "intensional definition") is in effect simply the conjunction of each of the criteria associated with the various members of SET-OF-COLS. This is what justifies the above description of INTERSECT as _the_ collection-intersection corresponding to SET-OF-COLS, and what justifies collectionIntersection's being defined as a functional predicate. See the corresponding function CollectionIntersectionFn; also see collectionUnion.
label: Collection Intersection
collectionIntersection

comment:
A binary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln1_3 RELN BINPRED) means that a formula built from RELN (i.e. a "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence and CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the first and third arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARG1 ARG3) holds. For further explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more general quaternary predicate interArgReln, which has two argument-places for specifying the pair of RELN's arguments that must be related by BINPRED.

If the relationship between the first and third argument is not a constraint, but should be inferred, use the related predicate: interArgReln_Inferred.

comment:
A binary predicate that relates Algorithms that are procedures for completing the same task(s) with respect to the same inputs -- i.e. algorithms that compute the same function (see algorithmComputes). (equivAlgorithms ALG1 ALG2) means that ALG1 and ALG2 have the same set of allowable inputs and, for any such input, they both produce the same output (or both produce no output). No further relationship is implied regarding the constituent operations or subAlgorithms of ALG1 and ALG2; only the initial inputs and final outputs are relevant.

For example, two different procedures for alphabetizing a list of names, or two explicit sets of directions for getting to the same destination from a given starting point, constitute equivalent algorithms, regardless of the details of either algorithm's internal structure.
label: Equiv Algorithms

comment: A TaxonomicSlot (q.v.) that relates things of any kind to collections (see Collection) of which they are instances. (isa THING COL) means that THING is an instance of the collection COL. isa is by far the most commonly-occurring predicate in the Cyc Knowledge Base, and is one of the relations most fundamental to the Cyc ontology. An important logical feature of isa is that it "transfers through" genls (q.v.): (isa THING COL) and (genls COL SUPERCOL) jointly imply (isa THING SUPERCOL). This logical feature is expressed in a rule that -- along with various other rules that also sanction the derivation of isa sentences -- has been asserted to the Knowledge Base. As a result, only a small fraction of the isa based ground atomic formulas (or "GAF"s; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence) the Cyc system "knows" to be true have been manually asserted; the vast majority have been derived, or are derivable, automatically by the Cyc inference engine via the use of such rules. See also elementOf.
label: is a

comment:
(controls AGENT THING) means that AGENT has effective control over THING. This does not mean that AGENT is at every moment directly affecting THING, but that AGENT can and will intervene when necessary. However, it does mean that AGENT must exercise some form of influence over THING at some time. For instance, in the military, a superior officer stands in this relation to a subordinate under his command. The officer need not at every moment tell the soldier what to do, but will intervene to correct the subordinate's actions when needed. However, the officer does at the very least affect the soldier psychologically, or the superior does not have effective control.

Normally, when an agent is in control of something, the agent is held responsible for what that thing does, or what happens to it. Note that controls refers to a standing relation between an agent and thing, perhaps as a result of stable social or causal facts. Note also, however, that the thing controlled might be an event rather than an object, and in such cases the controller only controls the event while (i.e. some or all of the time during which) the event is taking place; thus it differs from an actor-slot like directingAgent, which continues to hold between a directing agent and the directed event even after that event is finished. For the relation of controlling an object during a particular action, see the actor-slot objectControlled.
label: controlling
controls

An instance of SpatialPredicate. (in_ContOpen OBJ CONT) means that OBJ is contained in CONT (so that CONT confines or holds OBJ in), but OBJ can be removed from CONT without having to open any portals in CONT, break some part of CONT, or break OBJ into smaller pieces such that it can fit through some portal of CONT. Note that (in_ContOpen OBJ CONT) is a relationship based on the size of OBJ and the largest portal of CONT through which OBJ might be able to move. For example, a paperclip might be in_ContOpen a jail cell even though the person locked inside would be in_ContClosed (q.v.) the jail cell. This is because the paper clip is small enough to fit in between the bars of the cell, whereas the person is not.

comment:
This predicate is used to state that the value of a fluent remains constant for a fixed object throughout an event. (increasesThroughoutEvent_Fluent FLUENT EVENT) is true if and only if for every pair of sub-events SUB1 and SUB2 of EVENT there exist values VAL1 and VAL2 such that if 
(and
  (startsAfterEndingOf SUB1 SUB2)
  (valueOf (MeasurementAtFn FLUENT SUB1) VAL1))
  (valueOf (MeasurementAtFn FLUENT SUB2) VAL2))
it follows that 
(lessThan VAL1 VAL2)
is true. See also decreasesThroughoutEvent_Fluent and constantThroughoutEvent_Fluent.

A binary predicate that is used to state that a certain situation's obtaining ensures the truth or inevitabilty of a certain proposition. (ensures_SitProp SIT SENT) means that the (presupposed) fact that SIT obtains or occurs guarantees that SENT is or will become true. This implies that SENT expresses a contingent truth: although SENT is or will be true, it might not have been true (and perhaps but for SIT would never have been true). Note that SIT must play a material and decisive role in SENT's being or becoming true; it is not sufficient (or necessary) that SIT be a situation in which some agent verifies or becomes convinced of the truth or inevitability of SENT. For example, if the Tigers win a game that clinches them a spot in the playoffs, then that win ensures that the sentence 'The Tigers are in the playoffs' will (come playoff time) be true. See also ensures_AgentProp.
label: ensuring
ensures-SitProp

comment:
A specialization of the predicate expressesAlgorithms that relates an InformationBearingThing (q.v.) to a "maximal" algorithm that it expresses or fully describes. (expressesMaxAlgorithm IBT ALGORITHM) means that IBT unambiguously describes each operation in ALGORITHM and does not express (see expressesAlgorithms) any proper superalgorithm (see subAlgorithms) of ALGORITHM. IBT might be a written or spoken set of directions, an instance of ComputerProgramCopy, or something else.

Any agent or machine capable of interpreting IBT should be able, upon doing so, actually to carry out ALGORITHM on any allowable input (assuming that the agent or machine possesses the knowledge or abilities required to perform each operation in ALGORITHM).

Note that, in general, an IBT might express more than one maximal algorithm (e.g. a page might have instructions for two separate algorithms printed on it). A computer program copy, however, expresses exactly one maximal algorithm: the maximal algorithm used by the code for the copy.
label: Expresses Max Algorithm

comment:
A CollectionSalientAttributePredicate and specialization of collectionSalientAttribute_Represented. (collectionSalientAttribute_VirtuallyRepresented COL ATTR) means that ATTR is something (often a predicate, but possibly a function or collection-type) that is or corresponds to a salient attribute of COL that is at present not explicitly represented in the CycL language by a reified term, but that is readily representable by some reifiable CycL term constructable in the current CycL vocabulary. Thus, anything in the extent of this predicate represents a straightforward opportunity to expand the expressivity of the CycL language in a useful way.

For more details, see the specializations of this predicate, viz. #$collectionSalientDisjointWith, #$collectionSalientPartitions, collectionSalientSharedFeatureAssertions, #$collectionSalientFacetingBinPredVersion, and #$collectionSalientFacetingBinPredInverseVersion.

comment: (contrastedFeelings EMOTYPE CONTTYPE) means that a feeling of the type EMOTYPE differs in enough components from a feeling of the type CONTTYPE that it is unlikely (but not virtually impossible, as in the case of contraryFeelings) that someone would simultaneously experience feelings of both types EMOTYPE and CONTTYPE, especially with respect to the same object. E.g., (contrastedFeelings Pride Remorse), (contrastedFeelings Abhorrence Respect), (contrastedFeelings Entertained_Emotion Panic), etc. That last assertion expresses the rule of thumb that one does not often feel both entertained and panicy at the same time, though those two emotions are clearly not each other's `opposite' by any means.

comment:
A binary predicate that relates an instance of ComputerFile_CW (which may be a program or a LibraryFile) to an instance of ProperNameString. (executableProgramName PROGRAM EXE-NAME) means that EXE-NAME is a string used as the executable name for the computer program PROGRAM. EXE-NAME is the name that the package manager on a computer uses to keep track of programs that are installed. Note that the way Windows operating systems use executable names is case-insensitive, whereas for UNIX systems it is case-sensitive.

Also note that for many programs that run in UNIX environments the 'executable name' may actually only name a startup script which launches the program proper. This is the case, for instance, with Mozilla_TheProgram, where "mozilla" is a startup script which launches "mozilla-bin", which does the real work.
label: Executable Program Name
executableProgramName

comment: (deviceTypeManipulates USER-DEV INPUT-DEV) means that instances of USER-DEV are designed to 'operate on' or manipulate instances of INPUT-DEV. INPUT-DEVs are separate devices, not physical or functional components of USER-DEVs. The manipulation (mechanical or electrical) of INPUT-DEVs is central to the operation of USER-DEVs. INPUT-DEVs are typically inserted into USER-DEVs. Examples of the deviceTypeManipulates relationship include staplers and staples, guns and bullets, and media playing/recording devices and their media (e.g., CD players and CDs). Note that INPUT-DEV must itself be a device of some sort -- cooking containers do not operate on food, or garden hoses on water, in this sense. Also, devices and their remote-controllers are not examples.
label: Device Type Manipulates
deviceTypeManipulates

comment: This predicate is a generalization of instrument_Generic that relates an event (or other temporal situation) to an individual that plays an instrumental role in it (or in bringing it about). (instrumentalRole SIT INSTR) means that INSTR is used (in a broad sense of `used') by the "doer" DOER of SIT in order to "do" (or bring about) SIT. DOER will usually (but not necessarily) be an Agent_Generic. If SIT is an Event, DOER is s/he who (or that which) fills the doneBy actor slot with respect to SIT. If SIT is a StaticSituation, DOER is somebody who (or something that) is both a primary situationConstituents of SIT and has played a salient causal role in bringing SIT about (see causalActors). Consider a situation of George W. Bush napping on his cot; whether this is construed as an event or as a static situation, Bush would be its "doer" in the present sense and the cot would be playing an instrumentalRole. If SIT is an event and INSTR is partially tangible, use instrument_Generic or a specialization thereof. But if SIT is a static situation or INSTR is an intangible individual (such as a CommunicationConvention or a Letter_CW), instrumentalRole itself might need to be used. For a type-level version of this predicate, see instrumentalRole_Type.
label: Instrumental Role
instrumentalRole

An example shows a technical difference between northOf and fartherNorthThan: the CityOfRioDeJaneiroBrazil is fartherNorthThan the CityOfMelbourneAustralia, even though the shortest air route from Melbourne to Rio is to fly directly south (almost over the #$SouthPole).

A binary predicate relating an event in which things are ditributed to the source from which the distribution takes place. For example, in an event of spraying an aerosol from a can, the can is the source of the dispersion: (dispersionSource Spraying001 Can001). Similarly, if the explosion of a bomb, Bomb001, causes the distribution-of-shrapnel event, Dist001, then (dispersionSource Dist001 Bomb001) is true. Despite the lack of rules to enforce this, not every pair of an instance of PhysicalDistributionEvent and the instance of PartiallyTangible where the distribution intuitively originates will satisfy dispersionSource. For example, although Lake Itasca is the headwaters of the Missippi, and therefore in a sense the source of the (very long duration) event in which the Mississippi flows into the Gulf of Mexico, it is not true that (dispersionSource FlowOfTheMississippi Itasca), and not just because there are tributaries of the Mississippi that themselves have source this is not the right kind of distribution event to have a dispersionSource. Finally, note that dispersionSource is interesting primarily not for its own sake, but rather for the sake of enabling interesting restrictions to be put on kinds of instances of PhysicalDistributionEvent.
label: dispersion source

comment:
A specialization of derivedConceptualWork (q.v.) that relates a WorkingDraft (q.v.) to the published TextualPCW (q.v.) of which it is an earlier draft. (draftOfTextualWork DRAFT WORK) means that DRAFT is an earlier draft of WORK.

A working draft typically undergoes numerous changes, or revisions, before a finished work is produced and published. Thus the boundary between a working draft and the finished product is quite fuzzy. In some cases it is difficult or impossible to say, even in hindsight, whether a work that existed at some earlier time constitutes (or constituted) a different work than a particular later work we know today, or was instead simply that latter work itself at a less-than-ultimate stage in its evolution. In the former case, the two works will be related by draftOfTextualWork; in the latter case, there are not two works at all, but just one (that has been altered over time) and draftOfTextualWork, being asymmetric, does not apply. But often the context will make it clear that a particular work is considered to be a distinct, earlier draft of some published work.
label: Draft Of Textual Work
draftOfTextualWork

A substance's ceiling is the maximum concentration of the substance to which a normal, healthy human adult should be exposed to at any moment in time. comment:
An ActorSlot that relates a "transfer" event of any sort (see GeneralizedTransfer) to a spatial path (see Path_Spatial) that is followed during at least part of the event. More formally, (genericPathway_Partial TRANS PATH) means that at least part of the route of TRANS is spatial, and at least part of this part follows a part of PATH.

For example, if a certain trip TRANS takes a person from a home in Austin to one in Dallas via (mostly) I-35, part of the trip may occur along highways other than I-35 and part of it will occur along ordinary streets in Austin and Dallas. Thus only part of TRANS occurs along I-35. We may represent this in CycL by stating (genericPathway_Partial TRANS Interstate35). As another example, consider an e-mail sent from one PC to another. Suppose this transfer of information INFOTRANS occurs along several distinct cables. If one of these cables is CABLE001, then we may correctly assert (genericPathway_Partial INFOTRANS CABLE001).

See also genericPathway_Complete and its #$cyclistNotes for a comparison with this predicate. Note that in both examples above, it would be incorrect to replace genericPathway_Partial with genericPathway_Complete, since the entire transfers did not occur along I-35 and CABLE001, respectively.

See also the more specific predicates infoPathway_Partial and motionPathway_Partial.
label: partial pathway used
genericPathway-Partial

comment: (groupCohesion GROUP DEGREE) indicates that the members of the group GROUP have the degree DEGREE of loyalty to GROUP. Group loyalty may be based on a variety of motives. For example, in a business the degree of groupCohesion may depend upon the extent to which its employees desire the success of the business. In a military organization groupCohesion may depend upon the extent to which its members believe in the purpose or purposes for which the organization exists. In a criminal organization it may depend upon how much the members can benefit from the success of the organization's endeavors. Note that a particular degree of groupCohesion does not imply any degree of loyalty between members of the group on an individual level. For example, a criminal organization may have a high degree of groupCohesion but this does not imply that any one member will be loyal to other members where the success or well-being of the organization is not at stake. See also #$Loyalty-Status.

comment:
An EquivalenceRelation that holds between UnitOfMeasures (q.v.) that are interconvertible. (interconvertibleUnits UNIT1 UNIT2) means that any Quantity (q.v.) measured by UNIT1 can also be measured in UNIT2 (and vice versa), and there is some constant multiplication factor CONV for converting any UNIT1 measurement into an equivalent UNIT2 measurement (see unitMultiplicationFactor). That is, for any number (or other NumericInterval, or pair of such intervals) NUM, the following holds:

(equals (TimesFn (UNIT1 NUM) CONV) (UNIT2 NUM)) .

For example, Meter and Inch are interconvertible units since they both measure Distances: any measurement given in meters can be converted into a measurement given in inches, and vice versa. Conversely, neither of those units are interconvertible with Kilogram, which is a measure of Mass rather than distance.

Units-of-measure are interconvertible if and only if they are both instances of the same InterconvertibleUnitType (q.v.). Also see numericallyComparable.
label: Interconvertible Units
interconvertibleUnits
