This generic predicate relates a thing (individual or type) to where it comes from. (comesFrom_Generic THING WHENCE) means that THING comes from WHENCE. That is, either (i) WHENCE is THING's (or THING's instances') place of origin/creation (see e.g. birthPlace) or (ii) WHENCE is where THING (or its instances) currently hails from (see e.g. residesInRegion). The words `place' and `where' are used in a very broad sense here, to include not only geographical regions, but also physical objects (even people: "This bread comes from my mother") and events ("This ashtray came from the '39 World's Fair").

comment:
A TaxonomicSlot predicate that relates Collections (q.v.) that have no instances in common. (disjointWith COL1 COL2) means that COL1 is disjoint with COL2: nothing is an instance of both. That is, there is no THING such that both (isa THING COL1) and (isa THING COL2) hold. For example, (disjointWith Herbivore Carnivore) holds because no animal is both a herbivore and a carnivore. Note that disjointWith is not irreflexive (see IrreflexiveBinaryPredicate): it is possible for a collection to be disjoint with itself, though only if it is empty (i.e. has no instances). Thus, for example, (disjointWith Nothing Nothing) holds. Cf. intersectsWith.

Also note that it is quite possible for two second (or higher) order collections to be disjoint even if an instance of one collection and an instance of the other collection themselves share instances. Consider, for example, the disjoint collections SpatialThingTypeByShape and SpatialThingTypeByDimensionality. RoundObject is an instance of the first and ThreeDimensionalThing is an instance of the second; and any solid spherical object is an instance of both of these latter collections.
label: Disjoint With
disjointWith

label: Has Pollution Intensity
hasPollutionIntensity

comment: (in_ContClosed OBJ CONT) means that PartiallyTangible OBJ is completely contained within one or more cavities within SolidTangibleThing CONT, and that it is not possible for OBJ to leave CONT as an object without either the opening of a portal in CONT or the non-standard significant deformation of OBJ or CONT. CONT need not have a portal. Parts of OBJ may extend out through portals in CONT. If OBJ can temporarily undergo (a not-too forceful) shape deformation in order to fit through a portal in CONT, then OBJ is not in_ContClosed with respect to CONT. Positive examples include water in a bottle with a closed cap; a person in a closed jail cell sticking his arms through the bars; King Kong in a flimsy cage; a model of a ship in a bottle (where the model must be disassembled to force it out); egg yolk in an egg shell. Negative examples include a morsel of bread in a prison cell (morsels are small enough to leave the cell by passing in between the bars of the cell -- use in_ContOpen); an egg yolk in an egg -- use internalParts; water in an open bottle (the necessary deformation is not forceful). A positive borderline example is a skinny person in a jail cell who could just barely manage to squeeze through the bars (the necessary deformations, although self-imposed, would be abnormal and unexpected). A negative borderline example is a spelunker who has crawled through a narrow passage into a cave (the deformations needed to get in (and therefore out) were self-imposed and not abnormal).
label: In Cont Closed
in-ContClosed

comment: Some relations (namely, instances of MacroRelation (q.v.)) can be defined in terms of more basic or primitive constructs. (expansion RELATION FORMULA) associates RELATION with the FORMULA that defines it. The arg2 is allowed to reference generic-argument keywords, such as :ARG1 :ARG2 which represent respectively the arg1 and the arg2 within uses of RELATION. For example, (expansion genls (implies (isa ?object :ARG1) (isa ?object :ARG2))) indicates that the gaf (genls Poodle Dog) is defined as (implies (isa ?object Poodle) (isa ?object Dog))). Importantly, the expansion-formula arg2 must be necessary and sufficient; it denotes the definition of the uses of relation arg1; there can be only one expansion for any relation. Furthermore, no two relations can share a common expansion; thus, there can be only one possible contraction from a formula that corresponds to an expansion into a compact form that references expandable relations. For example, (implies (isa ?object Poodle) (isa ?object Dog))) has the unambiguous contraction of (genls Poodle Dog). The expansion arg2 can (and should when possible) make use of relations that have expansions. Note that the example above references implies which would itself have the expansion (or (not :ARG1) :ARG2). Thus, the full expansion of a relation can involve recursive expansions. For example, the full expansion of genls would be (or (isa ?object :ARG1) (not (isa ?object :ARG2)))). No relation may reference itself (either directly or indirectly via recursion) in its expansion (or in its full recursive expansion). See ELRelation, TermMacroFunction, #$expansionAxiom.
label: Expansion
expansion

comment: (epidemicExposurePeriod EPI INTERVAL) means that the Epidemic EPI is the result of an ExposureToHarmfulSubstance, which occurs entirely within the TimeInterval INTERVAL. Epidemiologists investigating an InfectiousDiseaseEpidemic try to determine if there is a single source of the pathogen responsible for the outbreak. If there is, they try to determine where, when, and under what circumstances animals/people were exposed to the source of the pathogen. Gafs using epidemicExposurePeriod represent the temporal location of the exposure event responsible for a given Epidemic.

comment:
A RuleMacroPredicate that relates a given PredicateType to any Predicate that is a generalization (see genlPreds) of all instances of that type. (commonGenlPreds PREDTYPE PRED) means that, for any instance PREDINST of PREDTYPE, (genlPreds PREDINST PRED) holds. Thus the commonGenlPreds sentence is equivalent to (relationAllInstance genlPreds PREDTYPE PRED).

Note that commonGenlPreds is not to be confused with typedGenlPreds (q.v.).

commonGenlPreds

comment:
A binary MetaRelation predicate that links each GenericValueFunction (q.v.) with its corresponding GenericValuePredicate (q.v.). (correspondingGenericValuePredicate GENVALFUNC GENVALPRED) means that GENVALFUNC and GENVALPRED, by definition, represent the same "generic amount" with respect to arbitrary TotallyOrderedQuantityTypes (q.v.).

For example, this holds: (correspondingGenericValuePredicate LowAmountFn lowAmountOf) .
label: Corresponding Generic Value Predicate

comment: (designationOfInformation INFO CLASS) assigns a classification CLASS to the information INFO.

comment: (covers_Paintlike COATING OBJECT) means that COATING adheres to and covers OBJECT like a coat of paint. Since COATING adheres to OBJECT, COATING directly touches (see the predicate touches_Directly) OBJECT. COATING may be either dry (e.g., dried paint) or liquid (e.g., lubricant spread on a surface, like cooking oil on a baking pan). (covers_Paintlike COATING OBJECT) implies that COATING isn't more cohesive with itself than it is with OBJECT, so (if dry) it would tend to peel or flake off in small pieces, rather than as a whole.
label: Covers-Paintlike
covers-Paintlike

comment:
An instance of MacroRelation. (givingEventTypeOfType GIVING-TYPE TYPE) means that the specialization of GivingSomething, GIVING-TYPE is the collection of events in which an instance of TYPE, a specialization of PartiallyTangible, was the objectGiven.

(givingEventTypeOfType GiftGiving Gift) relates the collection of events GiftGiving to the type of thing given, Gift. See also GivingOfTypeFn.

givingEventTypeOfType

comment:
A BinaryPredicate that is used to state that a special relation holds between a FacetingCollectionType and a BinaryPredicate -- that the former is "based on" the latter in a specific way.

Where (facets_Generic COL FACET-COL), (facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPred FACET-COL BINPRED) means that for each X in FACET-COL, there is a Y such that, by the definition of X, X is the one and only specialization of COL that bears BINPRED to Y.

For example, (facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPred OrganizationTypeByActivityType characteristicActivityTypeOfOrganizationType) means that for all ORG-TYPE in OrganizationTypeByActivityType there is an ACT-TYPE such that only the specializations of ORG-TYPE (including ORG-TYPE itself) are the specializations of Organization that bear the characteristicActivityTypeOfOrganizationType relation to ACT-TYPE.

E.g., SugarManufacturingOrganization, an instance of OrganizationTypeByActivityType, is by definition the one and only specialization of Organization that bears characteristicActivityTypeOfOrganizationType to SugarManufacturing.

For cases in which the arguments of BINPRED are reversed, see facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPredInverse. See also facetBasedOnBinaryPred and #$SharedNoteOnFacetBasisPredicates.
label: Facet Based On Type Binary Pred
facetBasedOnTypeBinaryPred

comment: (gamePlayingType GAME ACTIVITY-TYPE) identifies ACTIVITY-TYPE as the collection of instances of PlayingAGame in which the game being played (see Game) is GAME. For example, (gamePlayingType Cricket_TheGame (PlayingFn Cricket_TheGame)) means that (PlayingFn Cricket_TheGame) is the collection of events in which people are playing cricket.

comment: (hasPhysicalAccess PERSON OBJ) means that person PERSON has access to the individual OBJ, such that PERSON can touch or manually manipulate OBJECT. Like hasAccess, this predicate is true whenever a person is capable of accessing the individual involved, regardless of whether it is permitted for him or her to do so. It can return true even if (not (isa PERSON (AccessorFn OBJ))). Unlike hasAccess, hasPhysicalAccess is not true when PERSON is not in close spatial proximity to OBJECT. For instance, hackers have physical access to the computers on their desks, and use them to get access to other computers to which they do not have physical access.
label: Has Physical Access
hasPhysicalAccess

comment: (hardPointsOnAircraft ?AIR ?NUM) means that ?NUM is the number of places on the fuselage and/or wings of the ?AIR, or aircraft, where armament can be fitted. These places are called "hardpoints". Some hardpoints may not be able to fit certain weapons, and some weapons cannot be caried in combinations with others, even if the weight is below the maximum allowed.

(groupMaxCardinality GROUP CARDINALITY) means that the instance GROUP of Group has at most CARDINALITY members. So for example, where (groupCardinality GROUP 5), then (groupMaxCardinality GROUP 5) and where (groupCardinality GROUP (Unity 3 5)), then (groupMaxCardinality GROUP 5).

comment:
A specialization of inputs and commitsForFutureUses that is used to state that an input (see inputs) to an event is incorporated into some output (see outputs) of that event, but remains recognizable rather than being destroyed. (inputsCommitted EVENT OBJECT) means that OBJECT exists before EVENT and continues to exist afterwards, and as a result of EVENT, OBJECT becomes incorporated into something created during EVENT. Once incorporated into the output of EVENT, OBJECT can't be independently incorporated in any other creation event.

For example, bricks that are used to build a wall continue to exist as bricks once the wall has been built. While a part of the wall, a brick cannot be used as an independent input in another creation event. (See also outputsCreated.)

Note that there is a grey area between inputsCommitted and inputsDestroyed; the less possible it is to take apart the relevant outputs of EVENT and get OBJECT back as an independent thing, the more likely it is that the relationship between EVENT and OBJECT should be inputsDestroyed, rather than inputsCommitted.
Mx4rwLSVCpwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: inputs incorporated into the end result
label: input incorporated into the end result
inputsCommitted

comment: (disproportionationReactionFor ELEMENT REACTION-TYPE) holds just in case instances of ELEMENT involved in reactions of type REACTION-TYPE are both oxidized (loses electrons) and reduced (gains electrons). For example, in the following unbalanced equation (MnO4(2-) --> MnO4- + MnO2) Mn's oxidation number changes from 6 to 7 in the first product and from 6 to 4 in the second product.
label: disproportionate chemical reaction
disproportionationReactionFor

For example, (illuminatedObjectTypeLightSourceType Sunlit Sun) means that every object/area illuminated by sunlight has a sun (on earth, that would be our sun (TheSun)) as the source of that illumination.

One feeling is contrary to another if they are opposed in almost all their components. See also contrastedFeelings. It would be very rare for someone to feel both an EMOTYPE and CONTTYPE at the same time, especially about the same thing/event/situation. E.g., (contraryFeelings Gloominess Cheerfulness), (contraryFeelings Respect Contempt), (contraryFeelings Shame Pride), and so on.
label: Contrary Feelings
contraryFeelings

comment: A reflexive and transitive BinaryPredicate that relates a Microtheory to a Microtheory. (genlMt SPEC-MT GENL-MT) means that SPEC-MT is a specialization or extension of GENL-MT. (Note that it need not be a proper specialization or extension.) In particular, this entails that everything that is true in GENL-MT is also true in SPEC-MT. This relation is sometimes expressed informally by saying that SPEC-MT "sees" GENL-MT.
label: Genl Mt
genlMt

For example, a particular rite of passage, such as receiving a tribal tattoo, might instantiate a cultural practice of that tribe, and thus occur as part of that tribe's belief system. To relate religious ceremonies to their respective religions, use ceremonyOfReligion.

ceremonyOfBeliefSystem

groupQuarantined
comment: (groupQuarantined QUARANTINE ORGANISMS) means that the Group ORGANISMS are among those (not necessarily only those) that are quarantined by QUARANTINE. ORGANISMS includes only those organisms which are in in fact confined by QUARANTINE. To describe a group as subjected to a Quarantine, irrespective of whether all members of that group are in fact confined, use groupSubjectToQuarantine. To say of a single organism that it is confined in a certain Quarantine, use organismsQuarantined. For the location of a Quarantine, used quarantineLocation.

SUPER may or may not completely surround SUB, as they may share an outer boundary (e.g., the UnitedStatesOfAmerica and Texas_State in the WorldGeographyDualistMt). Note that, if either argument to geographicalSubRegions is an instance of GeopoliticalEntity, the assertion must be made in WorldGeographyDualistMt or a more specialized microtheory. To relate two instances of GeopoliticalEntity, use the predicate geopoliticalSubdivision, if it applies. See also surroundsHorizontally and bordersOn.

An interestRate may be on some LoanAgreement or it may be on some other Agreement, such as a Stock.

comment: (interests_Prop AGENT PROP) means that in the context of the assertion, AGENT has a substantial stake in whether PROP is true or false. The interest may be 'pro' or 'con'--i.e., AGENT may want PROP to be true or AGENT may want PROP to be false. What is required is that agent care strongly about what the truth-value is. AGENT may be justified in doing so or not. interests_Prop is one of the weakest instances of PropositionalAttitudeSlot, and features several stronger predicates as specializations, notably biases, desires, intends, and goals.

interests-Prop

comment:
A binary RuleMacroPredicate and a specialization of genlInverse that relates a binary EL-only (see ELRelation_OneWay) predicate with its non-EL-only "inverse correlate". (elInverse PRED EL-PRED) means that whenever a sentence of the form (EL-PRED ARG1 ARG2) is used to make an assertion, the CycCanonicalizer "transforms" it into the logically equivalent form (PRED ARG2 ARG1), and the latter is what actually gets stored in the Knowledge Base.

For example, (genlInverse genls specs) entails that if I assert the sentence '(specs Animal Cat)', what gets stored in the KB is the sentence '(genls Cat Animal)'.
label: El Inverse
elInverse

comment: This predicate relates an object to its quantified extensions in space. (extensionParametersOfObject OBJ DIST) means that DIST is a magnitude in which OBJ is extended in some spatial dimension. When making assertions about a particular object use a more specific predicate whenever possible, e.g. heightOfObject, widthOfObject, diameterOfObject.

extensionParametersOfObject

comment: (keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestionFrom ?COL1 ?COL2) states that the constant ?COL1 should never be offered as a precision suggestion from the constant ?COL2. (See CycPrecisionSuggestor.) ?COL1 may, however, be offered as a precision suggestion from any other constant that it is normally offered as a precision suggestion from. For example, Queen_HeadOfState should NOT be offered as a precision suggestion from the constant #$FemalePerson, though it is a direct specialization of this constant and would normally be offered in this case. We do not want to make Queen_HeadOfState keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestion, though, because we DO want to offer it as a precision suggestion for Monarch_HeadOfState (of which Queen_HeadOfState is a direct spec). Therefore, (keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestionFrom Queen_HeadOfState #$FemalePerson) would be a reasonable assertion.
label: Ke Irrelevant Precision Suggestion From
keIrrelevantPrecisionSuggestionFrom

comment: '(hitTarget HIT VICTIM)' means that VICTIM is the person killed in the MurderForHire HIT.

hitTarget

comment: (chiefOfAirWingSafety AIRWING PERSON) means that in any launch wherein AIRWING is the controllingLaunchAuthority_USAF, PERSON has the responsibility for enforcing the Range Safety Operations Requirement (RSOR), for evaluating and issuing safety approval for personnel authorized to remain in hazardous launch areas, for providing Range Users with a Range Safety Launch Operations Approval Lettter no later than the Launch Readiness Review (LRR), and for providing the final Range Safety approval for the launch.

chiefOfAirWingSafety

comment: (executableByExpected_Type FILE-TYPE ACCOUNT) means that it is expected that the account ACCOUNT would be able to execute (see executableBy) some files of the type FILE-TYPE. See also executableByNotAmenable_Type.

executableByExpected-Type

comment: (heatOfVaporization SUBSTANCE AMOUNT) expresses a relation that holds between an instance of ChemicalSubstanceType and an amount of heat, typically expressed in (PerFn GramCalorie Gram). This is the AMOUNT of heat required to convert instances of SUBSTANCE from the liquid or solid state to its gaseous state, with no change in temperature, after its boilingPoint is reached. For example, (heatOfVaporization AceticAcid ((PerFn GramCalorie Gram) 96.7)) means that *after* a sample of AceticAcid has reached its boiling point of (DegreeCelsius 117), ((PerFn GramCalorie Gram) 96.7) are required to convert the sample from the liquid to gaseous state and this energy is absorbed by the conversion process, and additional heat would increase the temperature of the sample.
label: heat of vaporization
heatOfVaporization

comment:
A instance of SpecificEntryFormatPredicate (q.v.) that amounts to what might be called "interchangeability of coextensional arguments", taken in a broad sense whereby sets and collections (see SetOrCollection) as well as pairs of relations (see Relation) can be "coextensional". coextensionalEntryFormatInArgs can be used to characterize (truth-condition-wise) a given argument-place of a predicate that is constrained (semantic well-formedness-wise) to being filled with instances of only either Collection, SetOrCollection, or Relation. That is, the given argument- position's argIsa constraint (or the "intersection" of the position's argIsa constraints, if there are more than one) is to some (proper or improper) specialization of either SetOrCollection or Relation. Suppose that coextensionalEntryFormatInArgs holds of PRED with respect to its Nth argument-place, and that the sentence (PRED ... ARGN ...) is true. It follows that any sentence (PRED ... ARGN-PRIME ...) that differs from the first sentence at most in its Nth argument is true if and only if ARGN-PRIME is coextensional with ARGN.

"Coextensional" is here defined as follows. Collections are coextensional just in case they have exactly the same instances (see coExtensional); set-or-collections are coextensional just in case they have exactly the same elements (see coextensionalSetOrCollections); predicates are coextensional just in case they hold of exactly the same sequences of arguments; and functions are coextensional just in case they they are defined for exactly the same sequences of arguments and have the same value for any such sequence.

coextensionalEntryFormatInArgs is useful because sometimes a certain argument-place of a given predicate is constrained to be a collection or set-or-collection or predicate or function, and all that's essential to the predicate's holding, with respect to that argument place (and a given fixed array of arguments for its other argument places), is the (set-or-) collection's _extent_ (see extent), the predicate's "predicate-extent", or the function's domain-to-range correlations. Such argument-places should not have the format singleEntryFormatInArgs (q.v.), since it is possible for two different collections, or a set and a collection, or two different predicates, or two different functions to have the same extension. On the other hand, the format openEntryFormatInArgs (q.v.) would place no real restriction on such an argument-place. coextensionalEntryFormatInArgs characterizes such argument places appropriately.
label: Coextensional Entry Format In Args
coextensionalEntryFormatInArgs

comment: (in_ContGeneric OBJ CONT) means that OBJ is contained, confined, or held in CONT. OBJ is not a part of CONT. CONT has a cavity (see CavityWithWalls) and OBJ is at least partly within (see spatiallyIntersects) the interior of this cavity. If CONT moves, OBJ is, by default, caused to move so as to remain within that cavity (see movesWith). If OBJ leaves the confines of CONT, then either OBJ passes through some appropriately sized portal of CONT, or OBJ breaks into smaller pieces that themselves pass through appropriately sized portals of CONT, or OBJ breaks through a wall of CONT. CONT may function as an open or closed container with respect to objects of the size of OBJ. If CONT is closed with respect to OBJ, then in_ContClosed is the preferred more specific predicate. If CONT is open with respect to OBJ, in_ContOpen is preferred. If OBJ is a fluid which completely fills CONT (for example, a cup of coffee brimming over) then in_ContFullOf is more precise.
label: In Cont Generic

comment:
An instance of both TemporalPredicate and ModalPredicate that is used to state (in a somewhat indirect way) that a given sentence is true during a certain time period. (holdsIn TEMP SENT) means that SENT is true at every moment in the temporalExtent (q.v.) of the TemporalThing TEMP.

For example, the sentence (holdsIn (YearFn 2003) (hasPets #$Curtis #$Patches-Cat)) means that throughout all of the year 2003 Curtis had Patches as a pet. This entails (e.g.) that Curtis had Patches on 5 July 2003: 

  (holdsIn
    (DayFn 5 (MonthFn July (YearFn 2003)))
    (hasPets #$Curtis #$Patches-Cat)) .

Similarly, (holdsIn #$Patches-Cat (hasPets #$Curtis #$Patches-Cat)) means that Curtis has Patches as a pet for Patches's entire life.

See also the more general predicate holdsSometimeDuring.

Note that a sentence of the form (holdsIn TEMP (PRED ... ARGi ...)), where ARGi is a TemporalThing, does not in general imply that ARGi temporally subsumes or even temporally intersects TEMP. For example, (holdsIn (YearFn 2003) (awareOf #$Curtis GeorgeWashington)) obviously doesn't imply that GeorgeWashington was alive in 2003. ARGi's temporally subsuming TEMP does follow, however, if PRED is a CotemporalPredicate that is contemporaryInArg (q.v.) in its ith argument-place (as hasPets is, in both argument-places).

Note also that there are two other ways to temporally-qualify sentences in CycL, which do not involve using holdsIn (or holdsSometimeDuring). Both involve temporally qualifying the Microtheory in which the (otherwise unqualified) sentence is asserted, and either can be used to state something roughly equivalent to a holdsIn sentence. Consider the first Curtis/Patches example above. First, one could assert (hasPets #$Curtis #$Patches-Cat) in some microtheory MT such that (holdsInTime_Always MT (YearFn 2003)). Second, one could assert (hasPets #$Curtis #$Patches-Cat) in a microtheory MT' such that both (mtTimeIndex MT' (YearFn 2003)) and (mtTimeParameter MT' TimePoint) hold. This later method, being the most developed and well-supported, is generally preferred over the others.

Note finally that it would be incorrect to assert a sentence like (hasPets #$Curtis #$Patches-Cat) in a non-temporally-qualified microtheory like the BaseKB, since Curtis didn't have Patches when (e.g.) he was a young boy, let alone in 3500 BCE.
label: Holds In
holdsIn

comment: (cutLinkInSystem LINK SYS) means that LINK is a single link in the ConnectedPathSystem SYS whose removal would cause the system to be disconnected. Thus {LINK}, i.e., (TheSet LINK), is a link-cut-set in SYS. That is to say, (cutLinkInSystem LINK SYS) holds if and only if (linkCutSetInSystem (TheSet LINK) SYS) holds. Note that since SYS is a ConnectedPathSystem whenever (cutLinkInSystem LINK SYS) holds, it is easy to see that (cutLinkInSystem LINK SYS) holds if and only if (linkCutMinimalSetInSystem (TheSet LINK) SYS) holds.

comment: (detects SENSOR STUFF) means that instance SENSOR of Sensor has detected STUFF. Be mindful of the difference between detects and perceives; only Agent_PartiallyTangibles perceive, which is (partially) accomplished through the detection process via some Sensors to which they are related. So, for example, you are a perceiver, but your ears (or perhaps your auditory sense system as a whole) are detectors. Only tangible things, PhysicalEvents or PartiallyTangibles, can be detected

A binary MetaRelation that holds between relations and collections. evaluationResultQuotedIsa is primarily used to indicate that any value returned by a given evaluatable function is a quoted instance of a given collection. Where FUNC is a Function-Denotational, (evaluationResultQuotedIsa FUNC COL) means that FUNC returns a quoted instance of COL for any sequence of arguments for which FUNC is defined. That is, (quotedIsa (FUNC ARG1 ... ARGn) COL) holds for any sequence <ARG1, ..., ARGN> for which FUNC has a value. For example, '(evaluationResultQuotedIsa SubstringFn SubLString)' holds, and it entails (e.g.) '(quotedIsa (SubstringFn "ABC" 1 2) SubLString)'.
label: Evaluation Result Quoted Isa
evaluationResultQuotedIsa

comment: An instance of ActorSlot (q.v.) that is a specialization of deliberateActors. (directingAgent EVENT DIRECTOR) means that DIRECTOR deliberately controls or directs EVENT, typically by controlling other participants in EVENT (see controls). AGENT might or might not perform EVENT directly. If an agent other than DIRECTOR performs (see performedBy) EVENT, then that performer's actions in EVENT are controlled by at least one of EVENT's directing agents. (In many cases, of course, EVENT will have only one director.) Non-performing directors typically control the actual performers by communicating instructions (or orders, commands, etc.) to them. For example, (directingAgent PSOBicentennialConcertOfBeethovensNinth WilliamSteinberg) holds, because Steinberg was the conductor of that concert; he directed the many other musicians who performed in that event. Other examples are (directingAgent MassacreAtMyLai LtWilliamCalley) and (directingAgent TateLaBiancaMurders CharlesManson).
label: directing agent
directingAgent

comment: This predicate is intended to express the relation typically attributed to a pair of objects by phrases of the form: book x is an edition of the book y -- where x and y refer to ConceptualWorks, and to not to any particular copies of those works. Given enough information about the content of two books (including what is written prior to the bodies of the books), and information about their origins (publisher, author et al), it is typically easy to determine whether or not this relation obtains between two books. Typically when (editionOfBook EDITION LATEREDITION), EDITION and LATEREDITION will have a common title and author (or at east some common author -- an author might be added -- and at least some part of the title in common), and LATEREDITION will be asserted to be an edition of 2nd or higher order somewhere in the text preceding its body. There will few circumstances in which these criteria will not be satisfied in which (editionOfBook EDITION LATEREDITION) is true.

comment: This is a very general causal predicate that indicates that one thing influences the structure or pattern of another, directly or indirectly. (influencesStructure THING1 THING2) means that the pattern or structure of THING1 somehow causally affects, or has affected, the pattern or structure of THING2, and that had THING1 been arranged differently in certain ways, THING2 would therefore have been arranged differently. An example is where THING2 is a copy of THING1, or where THING1 is a computer program that controls the form of THING2. Contrast this with a mere correlation between the two structures (see correlatedStructures). Unlike the more specific sourcePatternFor predicate, influencesStructure does not require that any particular pattern in the source be preserved in the affected thing.

comment:
A binary PropositionPredicate that is used to state that an agent makes sure that something is the case. (ensures_AgentProp AGENT SENT) means that AGENT ensures that SENT is true: AGENT determines whether SENT is true and, if it's not, intentionally performs an action that causes SENT to become true. This implies that SENT expresses a contingent truth: although SENT is (at least upon being ensured) in fact true, it might not have been true (and perhaps wasn't true before being ensured). Typically, immediately before ensuring SENT, AGENT wants SENT to be true (and might even believe it's likely to be true already), but is not certain that it's true.

For example, I sometimes ensure that the back door is locked when I'm about to leave my house. First, I go and check the door. If I find it's locked, I'm done. Or, if it's unlocked, I lock it, and then I'm done.

See also ensures_SitProp.
label: ensuring
ensures-AgentProp

Thus TERM is not a creation template FORT (see creationTemplateFORTs) that is reified when the code is run, nor is TERM a term that will appear in any assertions that result from the running of the relevant code. Rather, TERM will be resolved to the appropriate term and that term will appear in the relevant assertions.

An ActorSlot and a specialization of objectActedOn that relates a given event to an object or material that is used in that event and thereby either "used up" (i.e. destroyed) or incorporated into another object. (inputs EVENT OBJECT) means that OBJECT is a pre-existing participant in (see preActors) the CreationOrDestructionEvent EVENT which, during and due to EVENT, is either destroyed (see inputsDestroyed) or incorporated into a new entity (see inputsCommitted).

For example, the pigments used to paint the Mona Lisa were inputs to Leonardo's painting process; however, his brushes were not inputs, even though they were changed a little by it. In general, in instances of Manufacturing, materials or objects are inputs if they find their way into the product manufactured or if they are destroyed in the manufacturing process (e.g. the coke used in manufacturing steel).

comment:
A MetaLanguagePredicate (q.v.) that relates CycLDenotationalTerm to their denotata: the things in the intended model of the CycL language that those terms denote or stand for. (denotes TERM THING) means that TERM denotes THING. TERM will often be explicitly quoted, by being wrapped in the syncategorematic quotation symbol 'Quote'. For example, the true sentence '(denotes (Quote Plato) Plato)' means that the CycL term 'Plato' denotes the person Plato. (Thus denotes's first argument-place is not "implicitly quoted"; cf. quotedArgument).

But note that the first argument of denotes might not be quoted at all. Suppose (e.g.) that the term 'Plato' were the CycL constant most beloved of Cyclists, and that a new constant 'CyclistsFavoriteConstant' were reified and defined so as to reflect this fact. Then 'CyclistsFavoriteConstant' would refer to the CycL constant 'Plato', which in turn denotes the man Plato; and so the sentence '(denotes CyclistsFavoriteConstant Plato)' -- which involves no quotation -- would be true.

Note also that not all CycL terms denote, not even all CycLClosedDenotationalTerms (q.v.). For example, the term '(BorderBetweenFn Canada Mexico)' fails to denote anything (except perhaps in certain counterfactual contexts).

Note finally that the sentence '(denotes Plato Plato)' is of course not true, as it means that the man Plato is a CycL term that denotes the man Plato, which is a patent falsehood since no man is a CycL term and no man denotes anything.

See also means, expresses, hasDenotatum, quotedIsa, EscapeQuote, and the shared #$NoteAboutQuotingInCycL.
label: Denotes
denotes

comment: (connectedViaFlexibleConnector OBJ1 OBJ2) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are connected via a connector which is flexable. OBJ1 and OBJ2 can move relative to each other due to deformation of the connector. This predicate is a specialization of connectedTo_SemiRigidly and a generalization of flapHingedTo. Positive exemplars are two objects conected by Velcro (tm), the GallBladder's connection to the Liver, or the front cover of a Book_CW's connection to that book's spine. Negative examples include a hypodermic needle's connection to the IV tube (the tube is flexible, not the connection), a door's connection to the door Frame (parts of the hinge rotate relative to other pars, but the hinge does not deform), and a Wheel's connection to an Axle (no deformation here, either).

So, expelledFromOrganization doesn't express the brute fact that AGT at some time in the past was expelled from ORG. Rather, it gives a status that can hold for some time interval and fail to hold at some later interval if they are allowed to rejoin. comment: This predicate can be used to state some particular thing that a given intelligent agent intends or has in mind as a purpose, represented as a propositional attitude. (intends AGENT SENT) means that AGENT intends the proposition PROP expressed by SENT to become (or remain) true. This implies that AGENT believes s/he has at least some degree of influence or control over bringing about (or maintaining) the truth of PROP. While this predicate is obviously similar to goals (q.v.), AGENT's intending PROP is likely to be more short-term and event-centered ("I did it because I intended that...") and more mechanically satisfied ("I intend to turn off the lamp") than any of AGENT's goals. You may intend to turn off the lamp, but it would be odd to call that one of your goals. For a similar predicate that represents intending in relation to types of temporal situations, see intends_SitType.
label: intent

comment: (connectedTo_Rigidly OBJ1 OBJ2) means that OBJ1 and OBJ2 are joined so that no relative motion between them can occur at the point of connection unless the connection is severed by breakage of some part of the connected objects or by disassembly of the connection. Further, no relative motion between the contact surfaces of OBJ1 nor OBJ2 may occur. Thus, if a nail is rigidly connected to a board, the only way for that relationship to no longer hold is if the nail is pulled out of the hole (e.g. by a hammer or crowbar) or if the nail or board is broken in a critical location. Note that (connectedTo_Rigidly OBJ1 OBJ2) does admit cases in which OBJ1 or OBJ2 undergo plastic deformation. For example, consider the case of a disc rigidly connected via glue (see gluedTo) to a rubber sheet. The rubber sheet and disc may undergo significant relative motion. Both of the connected objects are solid.
label: Connected To Rigidly
connectedTo-Rigidly

comment: This predicate is used to illustrate examples of the raw data which may appear in tuples defined by a physical schema. That is, if SCHEMA is a physical schema (an instance of #$SKSSchema-Physical) and TUPLE is a tuple of data objects (an instance of Tuple) then (exampleTuple SCHEMA TUPLE) means that the elements of TUPLE satisfy the data type constraints of the physical fields of SCHEMA. However, TUPLE may or may not correspond to an actual record in a database or knowledge source implementing SCHEMA.

A MetaRelation predicate that relates instances of Relation to things in their ranges. (inRangeOf ELEMENT RELATION) means that ELEMENT is an element of the relationRange (q.v.) of RELATION. That is, RELATION relates at least one thing in its domain (see relationDomain and inDomainOf) to ELEMENT. If the relationalArity (q.v.) of RELATION is N (for N > 1), then ELEMENT is the Nth item of an N-length List that is an element of the extension (see relationExtension) of RELATION. (Note that if the relationalArity of RELATION is 1 then it has no range, and inRangeOf is undefined for such a RELATION.) If RELATION is a VariableArityRelation (q.v.) there will be no particular length N shared by each of the lists in its extension; but ELEMENT will still be the last item of some list in that extension.

Though this predicate can be applied to polyadic relations generally, asserting that something is in RELATION's range will normally be of particular interest only when RELATION is a function (i.e. an instance of Function_Denotational), in which case RELATION associates each element of its domain with exactly one element of its range. See also RangeOfFunctionFn.
label: In Range Of
inRangeOf

comment: A binary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln3_4 RELN BINPRED) means that a formula built from RELN (i.e. a "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence and CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the third and fourth arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ARG1 ARG2 ARG3 ARG4 ..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARG3 ARG4) holds. For example, (interArgReln3_4 #$candidateEngagementAreaOfCOAForForces opponents) means that the arg3 and arg4 in a #$candidateEngagementAreaOfCOAForForces assertion must be opponents. For further explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more general quaternary predicate interArgReln, which has two argument-places for specifying the pair of RELN's arguments that must be related by BINPRED.

Although, some could argue on the mere notion of creation of art objects, this predicate ignores such ratiocinations and attributes to objects typically belonging to museum's holdings a date, or a time interval, accepted by historians of art. comment:
(granuleOfSpatialStuff STUFFTYPE OBJTYPE) means that the stuff-like collection STUFFTYPE has as its spatial granules (or granularity level) instances of the object-like collection OBJTYPE. If some collection is spatially stuff-like, that means that the instances of that collection can be divided spatially, and the resulting physical portions will themselves be instances of that collection; e.g., a physical portion of some instance of SandMob is still sand (cf. ExistingStuffType). Such divisibility cannot go on indefinitely, however: eventually, division of something spatially stuff-like will result in the object-like 'granules' out of which the stuff-like thing is composed. For instances, division of sand would eventually result in individual grains of sand, division of water would eventually get down to individual molecules of water, etc.

_Below_ this level of division, the remaining physical portions do _not_ count as instances of the stuff-type from which they were divided. _At_ this level of division, things may go one way or another: a single molecule of water is Water (at least if we stick by the necessary identity of water and H2O), whereas a single grain of sand is not plausibly sand.
label: Granule Of Spatial Stuff
granuleOfSpatialStuff

   (SubExpressionAtOffsetFn PEG-N "an emu" 11) 
   (SubExpressionAtOffsetFn PEG-N "emu" 14))

label: Expression Head
expressionHead

comment: An assertion of the form (#$endsAfterEndingOfTempStage TEMP-STAGE1 TEMP-STAGE2) is used to relate two instances of TemporalStageSpecification. Both will be part of the representation of some type of Situation SIT-TYPE, and so will bear the relation siblingSpecifications to one another. This assertion combines with other assertions (most importantly with the predicates sitTypeHasTemporalStage and situationFallsUnderStage) to provide a type-level description of the temporal ordering of the subsituations of the instances of SIT-TYPE. comment: A predicate used for probability statements. (derivedProbability_Range PROPOSITION PROBRANGE) means that, in the applicable Microtheory, the a posteriori probability of the truth of the formula PROPOSITION, given (and depending on) the current state of knowledge of all other assertions, is somewhere in the range PROBRANGE (either a real number between zero and one, where zero means certainly false and one means certainly true, or an interval between two such numbers). In most microtheories, generally, this refers to the derived range of derived probability that PROPOSITION is true given the probabilities (or probability ranges) of the other CycLAssertions and domainAssumptions of the Microtheory. Contrast this with priorProbability_Range and with derivedProbability. A derivedProbability_Range depends at least partially on, and is in some manner derived from or affected by, the probabilities of some or all of the other CycLAssertions in the Microtheory (whether prior, derived or conditional) along with the domainAssumptions. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.
label: Derived Probability Range
derivedProbability-Range

comment:
A MetaPredicate for stating that one predicate is a generalization of another. (genlPreds SPEC-PRED GENL-PRED) means that GENL-PRED is a generalization of SPEC-PRED. That is, (GENL-PRED ARG1..ARGN) holds whenever (SPEC-PRED ARG1..ARGN) holds. For example, (genlPreds touches near) holds, as touching something implies being near it.

As for the respective arities (see arity) of SPEC-PRED and GENL-PRED, (i) both predicates might have the same fixed-arity (see FixedArityRelation), (ii) both might have variable-arity (see VariableArityRelation), or (iii) SPEC-PRED might have a fixed-arity and GENL-PRED variable-arity. (It cannot be the case that SPEC-PRED has variable-arity and GENL-PRED has a fixed-arity.)

See also negationPreds, genlInverse, and negationInverse.

comment:
A binary MetaKnowledgePredicate that relates an EpistemologicalLevelRelation (q.v.) predicate to a non-EL-only predicate that is (one of) its "canonicalization-transform"(s). (elCorrelates PRED EL-PRED) means that whenever a sentence of the form (EL-PRED . ARGS) is used to make an assertion, the CycCanonicalizer "transforms" it into a logically equivalent sentence (... (PRED . ARGS-PRIME) ...) in which the CycL term for PRED occurs but that for EL-PRED does not; and the latter sentence is what actually gets stored in the Knowledge Base.

For example, (elCorrelates genls specs) holds because a sentence of the form (specs GENL SPEC) gets canonicalized into one of the form (genls SPEC GENL). And (elCorrelates abnormal exceptWhen) holds because a sentence of the form (exceptWhen EXCEPTION RULE) (where X1,..., Xn are all the variables that occur free in both EXCEPTION and RULE) gets canonicalized into a sentence of the form 

  (implies
    EXCEPTION
    (abnormal (TheList X1 .... Xn) RULE)) .

These examples illustrate two noteworthy points. First, the arguments to EL-PRED in the pre-canonicalizer sentence, while they might not be exactly the same, or be in the same order, as those of PRED in the post-canonicalizer sentence, will all typically appear somewhere in the latter sentence. Second, while the pre- and post-canonicalizer sentences are logically eqivalent, PRED and EL-PRED themselves might be equivalent (modulo a permutation in argument-order) or might not be.

Note that elCorrelates is not functional in either argument-place. E.g. it relates abnormal to both of the exception predicates exceptWhen and exceptFor, and it relates both pragmaticallyNormal and meetsPragmaticRequirement to the exception predicate pragmaticRequirement.

An important specialization of elCorrelates is elInverse (q.v.).
label: El Correlates
elCorrelates

The predicate ingredients is used to indicate a particular input used to make a particular artifact. (ingredients ART INGR) means that the PartiallyTangible thing INGR is one of the inputs in the creation of the Artifact ART, and INGR (or matter derived from it) is one of ART's physicalParts.

This is a general predicate that usually can be stated in a more specific manner. For example: ingredients_Separable applies only to those inputs which retain their identity in the creation process and which are incorporated into the resulting Artifact; ingredients_Constituent applies to ingredients that permiate the resulting Artifact; and ingredients_Destroyed refer to ingredients that have been transformed in the creation process.

comment: A PhysicalAmountSlot used for stating the heights of tangible objects and other (polydimensional) spatial things. (heightOfObject OBJECT HEIGHT) means that the Distance (q.v.) from OBJECT's bottom boundary to its top boundary is HEIGHT. "Top" and "bottom" are often determined by an object's intrinsic default orientation, if it has one (see TopAndBottomSidedObject). But some objects have tops and bottoms -- and thus heights -- only by virtue of their spatial relations to certain other objects in their environments. In any case, having a height requires being at least two-dimensional (see PolyDimensionalThing). See also lengthOfObject, widthOfObject, and depthOfObject.

Note that the fedByConfluenceOfRivers relation does _not_ hold in cases where a smaller river feeds all by itself into (and thereby increases the volume of) a bigger river; for such cases use the more general tributaries.

For example, a particular instance of RainStormAsEvent may have distinguishable cotemporalSubEvents for (1) raining and (2) wind blowing, and an instance of swimming Backstroke has separable events for (1) kicking and (2) arm motion throughout the swimming. comment:
An AbsoluteLocationalPredicate and specialization of notFarFrom that relates a GeographicalThing to a GeographicalSpaceRegion (qq.v.) such that part of the former is located at a part of the latter. (genericallyLocatedAt_SurfaceGeographical OBJ GEOSPACE) means that part of OBJ is exactly located at a part of GEOSPACE. GEOSPACE corresponds to a set of pairs of geographical coordinates (i.e. degrees latitude and longitude) whose extent intersects the exact space on a planet's surface that is occupied by OBJ.

Note that partiallyLocatedAt_SurfaceGeographical is agnostic as to whether or not OBJ is (partially or wholly) located under, on, or above the ground at GEOSPACE (see locationState); that is why this predicate is not a specialization of spatiallyIntersects. Also note that this predicate assumes a planetary FrameOfReference, typically PlanetEarth and the TerrestrialFrameOfReference.

See also the specializations partiallyLocatedAt_SurfaceGeographical and whollyLocatedAt_SurfaceGeographical.

comment: A binary InterArgRelnPredicate (q.v.). (interArgReln3_1 RELN BINPRED) means that a formula built from RELN (i.e. a "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedAtomicSentence and CycLClosedNonAtomicTerm) is semantically well-formed only if BINPRED holds between the third and first arguments to RELN (in that order) in the GAF/NAT. That is, a formula (RELN ARG1 ARG2 arg3 ..) is semantically well-formed only if (BINPRED ARG3 ARG1) holds. For further explanation of semantic well-formedness, see CycLExpression_Assertible and its direct specializations. See also the more general quaternary predicate interArgReln, which has two argument-places for specifying the pair of RELN's arguments that must be related by BINPRED. Use interArgReln_Inferred to conclude that (BINPRED ARG3 ARG1) holds.
label: Inter Arg Reln 3 1
interArgReln3-1

comment: An instance of SpatialPredicate. (in_ContFullOf CONTAINED CONTAINER) means that CONTAINED is located in CONTAINER, and, moreover, that CONTAINED fills CONTAINER. That CONTAINED fills CONTAINER implies that the inside surface of CONTAINER touches CONTAINED at virtually all points of that surface. In order to fill CONTAINER, CONTAINED must either be something that can easily conform itself to the shape of CONTAINER, or something with a relatively rigid shape that happens to fit CONTAINER.

in-ContFullOf

comment: (correspondingSequences LIST1 LIST2) means that LIST1 is a list of of deoxyribonucleotides and LIST2 is a corresponding sequence of ribonucleotides. The coding sequences of ribonucleic acid molecules (see RNAMolecule) differ from the coding sequences of deoxyribonucleic acid molecules (see DNAMolecule) in that the nucleic acid thymine in DNA is replaced by the ribonucleic acid uracil in RNA. Corresponding sequences in DNA and RNA molecules are thus coding sequences that are identical, save that where 'T' appears in the nucleic sequence, 'U' appears in the ribonucleic sequence.
label: Corresponding Sequences
correspondingSequences

comment: (jurisdictionOverIndividual AGENT THING) means that the LegalAgent AGENT has jurisdiction over the PartiallyTangible THING. This is a high level and vague notion of jurisdiction that will fill a gap in the KB until the notion of jurisdiction can properly be dissected into its more specific meanings. Proper use of this constant, for example, would be to express that a government AGENT has jurisdiction over a citizen of that government, THING. Even though the arg constraints are very loose, however, this constant is not to be used to say that a person has jurisdiction over their hand.

An ActorSlot and specialization of genericPathway_Partial that relates an InformationTransferEvent to a Path_Spatial that is followed, at least in part, during the event. (infoPathway_Partial TRANS PATH) means that part of the route of TRANS is spatial and follows part of PATH.

comment: An instance of IRExpansionPredicate. (irExpansionCandidate_Terse THING EXPANSION-CANDIDATE) says that EXPANSION-CANDIDATE is an instance of CycLTerm that can be used to generate NL strings to be added to an IR search containing strings that denote THING. For example, (irExpansionCandidate_Terse BillClinton UnitedStatesPresident) says that generation strings for UnitedStatesPresident (e.g., "United States president" can be added to an IR search string that contains a reference to Bill CLinton, such as "President Clinton" or (in the right context) "he". Values for EXPANSION-CANDIDATE are calculated by looking for nearest isa/genls, most-notable isa/genls, and nearest #$qaClarifyingCollections for THING. As such, irExpansionCandidate_Terse embodies a simple, context-free set of hueruistics to supply a relatively terse list of expansion candidate terms. For more information, see the #$SharedNoteOnIRExpansionGeneration.

comment:
An IrreflexiveBinaryPredicate and a specialization of temporallyCoexist. Where THING1 and THING2 are both instances of PartiallyTangible, (fitsInsideObject THING1 THING2) means that THING1 can fit inside THING2. For example: 
  (fitsInsideObject Joe JoesCar)
  (fitsInsideObject JoesCar JoesGarage)
  (not (fitsInsideObject JoesGarage JoesCar))
  (not (fitsInsideObject PlanetEarth JoesGarage))
More specifically, (fitsInsideObject THING1 THING2) means that, in principle at least, one could make it the case that (in_ContCompletely THING1 THING2) without altering the physical structure of THING1 or THING2 in an atypical way.

The italicized clause is vague but nevertheless quite important. Consider, for example, an inflatable raft, RAFT, that comes packaged (deflated) in a small (say, 20 cm x 30 cm) cardboard box, BOX. Even when RAFT is inflated, it is true that (fitsInsideObject RAFT BOX), since one could deflate the raft and put it into the box (and to deflate the raft would not be to alter its physical structure in an atypical way). Now suppose that STICK is a (non-collapsible) wooden meter stick. It is false that (fitsInsideObject STICK BOX); for one could make it the case that (in_ContCompletely STICK BOX) only by changing the physical structure of STICK or BOX in an atypical way (e.g. by breaking STICK into pieces or radically altering the shape of BOX).
label: Fits Inside Object
fitsInsideObject

comment: The predicate genlRoles relates two Cyc constants representing Roles. (genlRoles SP-ROLE GEN-ROLE) indicates that the role GEN-ROLE is a general characterization of another role SP-ROLE. If an object plays the more specific role SP-ROLE in a situation, it thus also fills the more general role GEN-ROLE. For example, in a Microtheory representing the use of a dishwasher, a genlRoles of #$TheDishes is #$TheObjectActedOn, and a genlRoles of #$TheWashCycle is #$TheSubEventRole.
label: Genl Roles

comment:
A symmetric binary MetaPredicate that is a specialization of genlInverse (q.v.). (inverseBinaryPredicateOf BINPRED INVPRED) means that BINPRED and INVPRED are inverses of each other. That is, (BINPRED ARG1 ARG2) holds if and only if (INVPRED ARG2 ARG1) holds.

Furthermore, we stipulate that the respective argument-type constraints on BINPRED and INVPRED are such that a given thing is an admittedArgument (q.v.) to BINPRED's first (second) argument-place if and only if it is an admittedArgument to INVPRED's second (first) argument-place.

See also the corresponding function InverseBinaryPredicateFn.

forecastedAmbientVisibility

comment: (dialects LANGUAGE DIALECT) means that DIALECT is a dialect of the language LANGUAGE.
label: Dialects (asymmetric binary predicate)
dialects

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function ExplanationFn. (explanationOf X (ExplanationFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Explanation Of
explanationOf

comment: (cblSendMessageNamed SEND-COMMAND PROGRAM-IDENTIFIER) means that CycBehaviorLanguage SEND-COMMAND sends the message identified by PROGRAM-IDENTIFIER.
label: Cbl Send Message Named
cblSendMessageNamed

comment: (eMailSourceAddress MSG ADDRESS) means that the EMailAddress ADDRESS is the source address for an EMailMessage MSG. Note that a single message has exactly one source address, and that address can never be changed. A message with the same content but a different address is still a different instance of EMailMessage (although the same instance of EMailMessageText might be a part of it).
label: E Mail Source Address
eMailSourceAddress

comment: (jobPositionOpeningStatus JOB OSTATUS) means JobPosition JOB has the #$OpeningStatusOfJobPosition OSTATUS. The latter can be: JobOpen and JobFilled.
label: Job Position Opening Status
jobPositionOpeningStatus

comment: A MeasurableQuantitySlot and TimeDependentRelation that relates a LegalCorporation to a MonetaryValue. (corpShare52WeekRange CORP RANGE) means that RANGE is the range of prices at which shares of CORP have traded over the past 52 weeks.
label: 52-week range
corpShare52WeekRange

comment: The predicate corresponding to GoalOfVerifyingHypothesizedInfoAboutTopicFn (q.v.).
label: Goal Type Of Verifying Hypothesized Info About Topic
goalTypeOfVerifyingHypothesizedInfoAboutTopic

comment: The predicate hasPatients represents a relationship between a medical professional and a patient (including nonhuman animals). (hasPatients MEDIC PATIENT) means that the MedicalCareProvider MEDIC is treating the recipient-of-care PATIENT. PATIENT may be a human or a nonhuman animal. An assertion using hasPatients holds only during the time that PATIENT has a condition that is being treated by MEDIC; it does not represent or imply a long term doctor-patient relationship.
label: Has Patients
hasPatients

comment: An instance of IRExpansionPredicate. (irExpansionSet_Definitional_CoarseGrained TERM SET) identifies SET as the set of terms that make up the definitional (isa and generalizations) terms for TERM. For example, where TERM = hasPets, SET will have among its elements BinaryPredicate, owns, and Thing.
label: Ir Expansion Set Definitional Coarse Grained
irExpansionSet-Definitional-CoarseGrained

comment: (eventAffectsPlantPart EVT PART) says that EVT affects PlantPart PART. For example, (eventAffectsOrganismPart WeedingEvent562 RootSystem075) says that WeedingEvent562 affects RootSystem075.
label: Event Affects Plant Part
eventAffectsPlantPart
